WEBVTT

1
00:00:10.458 --> 00:00:16.208
BASED ON A TRUE STORY

2
00:00:24.791 --> 00:00:26.791
[muffled groaning]

3
00:00:31.958 --> 00:00:34.416
[man] <i>It all started with one tiny boat.</i>

4
00:00:40.958 --> 00:00:42.875
<i>Can we just let people drown?</i>

5
00:00:44.958 --> 00:00:46.791
[indistinct shouting]

6
00:00:46.875 --> 00:00:48.916
[man] <i>Can we actually look away?</i>

7
00:00:52.125 --> 00:00:54.708
<i>The thought flooded me.</i>

8
00:00:56.958 --> 00:00:59.083
<i>I felt it deeply. It wouldn't go away.</i>

9
00:01:00.708 --> 00:01:02.083
<i>It only got bigger.</i>

10
00:01:03.416 --> 00:01:05.750
<i>It got stronger and stronger.</i>

11
00:01:07.875 --> 00:01:09.666
<i>Till I couldn't break free from it.</i>

12
00:01:10.625 --> 00:01:12.666
[sighs]

13
00:01:12.750 --> 00:01:14.625
<i>We're facing 20 years in prison now.</i>

14
00:01:15.708 --> 00:01:18.750
["Disparate Youth" by Santigold playing]

15
00:01:19.750 --> 00:01:23.666
{\an8}SUMMER 2015

16
00:01:23.750 --> 00:01:25.333
{\an8}[excited chatter]

17
00:01:28.333 --> 00:01:31.500
{\an8}[upbeat electronic pop continues]

18
00:01:31.583 --> 00:01:33.291
{\an8}[laughing]

19
00:01:34.541 --> 00:01:37.166
{\an8}[laughs] Go. go. go. go! Yes!

20
00:01:37.250 --> 00:01:38.875
{\an8}-[exclaims]
-Go!

21
00:01:39.625 --> 00:01:40.916
{\an8}[laughing]

22
00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:45.250
{\an8}[woman yelps. giggles]

23
00:01:47.250 --> 00:01:49.000
{\an8}[both panting]

24
00:01:50.750 --> 00:01:52.000
[woman groans]

25
00:01:52.083 --> 00:01:54.500
-[sighs. laughs]
-[exhales]

26
00:01:55.375 --> 00:01:57.458
[man] <i>During the summer of 2015.</i>

27
00:01:57.541 --> 00:02:00.583
<i>hundreds of thousands of refugees</i>
<i>made their way to Germany and Europe.</i>

28
00:02:00.666 --> 00:02:02.250
-Take out the bottles?
-Mm-hmm.

29
00:02:06.416 --> 00:02:08.583
[man] <i>They were fleeing</i>
<i>from war and violence.</i>

30
00:02:08.666 --> 00:02:11.125
<i>hoping for protection and a better future.</i>

31
00:02:11.958 --> 00:02:13.833
-[man 2] Good morning.
-Morning.

32
00:02:15.291 --> 00:02:18.666
-Wow. you look great.
-You too.

33
00:02:18.750 --> 00:02:21.875
[man] <i>Despite great challenges</i>
<i>and a whole bunch of unanswered questions.</i>

34
00:02:21.958 --> 00:02:23.875
<i>a wave of compassion swept the country.</i>

35
00:02:23.958 --> 00:02:25.708
<i>There was a true willingness to help.</i>

36
00:02:25.791 --> 00:02:28.250
-[boy] No!
-Not a problem. It's all good.

37
00:02:28.333 --> 00:02:31.958
-It happens.
-[speaking Turkish] Sorry.

38
00:02:32.041 --> 00:02:33.708
It's really not a problem.

39
00:02:33.791 --> 00:02:36.250
<i>♪ We know now we want more ♪</i>

40
00:02:36.916 --> 00:02:38.583
<i>♪ Oh. ah ♪</i>

41
00:02:38.666 --> 00:02:40.500
-[indistinct chatter]
-<i>♪ Oh. ah ♪</i>

42
00:02:40.583 --> 00:02:42.750
<i>♪ A life worth fighting for ♪</i>

43
00:02:44.666 --> 00:02:47.791
<i>♪ So let them say we can't do better ♪</i>

44
00:02:51.166 --> 00:02:53.916
<i>♪ Lay out the rules that we can't break ♪</i>

45
00:02:57.166 --> 00:03:00.333
<i>♪ They wanna sit and watch you wither… ♪</i>

46
00:03:02.125 --> 00:03:03.291
-Hey there.
-What's up?

47
00:03:03.375 --> 00:03:05.791
I've got some food donations in here.

48
00:03:09.333 --> 00:03:11.458
[man] <i>The openheartedness didn't last.</i>

49
00:03:11.541 --> 00:03:16.000
<i>European governments grew overwhelmed</i>
<i>and decided to shut their borders.</i>

50
00:03:16.083 --> 00:03:18.125
<i>For many refugees. the only option left</i>

51
00:03:18.208 --> 00:03:20.750
<i>was to try and survive</i>
<i>an escape across the Mediterranean.</i>

52
00:03:20.833 --> 00:03:22.958
<i>There were no government rescue missions.</i>

53
00:03:23.041 --> 00:03:27.166
<i>Only one private ship attempted</i>
<i>to save people from drowning.</i>

54
00:03:28.291 --> 00:03:31.125
Hey. You want the ball?

55
00:03:31.208 --> 00:03:33.458
<i>♪ A life worth fighting for… ♪</i>

56
00:03:33.541 --> 00:03:34.458
[kids shouting]

57
00:03:34.541 --> 00:03:37.041
[man] <i>Even though</i>
<i>it seemed completely impossible…</i>

58
00:03:37.125 --> 00:03:39.375
-[girl shouts]
-[man groans]

59
00:03:39.458 --> 00:03:40.708
[man] <i>…I wanted to help.</i>

60
00:03:40.791 --> 00:03:42.833
[groans playfully. laughs] Ah. no! No!

61
00:03:42.916 --> 00:03:45.875
[group exclaims]

62
00:03:47.958 --> 00:03:51.666
-[woman] We saw that in one of my classes.
-Two? Two more. Emil!

63
00:03:51.750 --> 00:03:54.750
[woman] …where Europe ends.
and no one cares what happens beyond that.

64
00:03:54.833 --> 00:03:57.750
Until last year. there was
a government-funded rescue mission.

65
00:03:57.833 --> 00:04:01.250
The Mare Nostrum rescued
over 150.000 refugees a year.

66
00:04:01.333 --> 00:04:03.208
And it got canceled. So no more help.

67
00:04:03.291 --> 00:04:05.125
No one goes out
on rescue missions anymore.

68
00:04:05.208 --> 00:04:08.958
But there's like 150 people
in each of those rubber boats.

69
00:04:09.041 --> 00:04:11.625
Or over 1.000 people
in old wooden vessels.

70
00:04:11.708 --> 00:04:13.083
There isn't a single life jacket.

71
00:04:13.166 --> 00:04:16.541
If there's an incident. they all drown
'cause no one's there to help.

72
00:04:17.250 --> 00:04:21.291
So I was thinking.
there's got to be a way to get involved.

73
00:04:21.375 --> 00:04:23.208
Like buy a rescue ship.

74
00:04:25.583 --> 00:04:26.791
Buy an actual ship?

75
00:04:26.875 --> 00:04:29.541
Yeah. I think it's possible.
I've seen a ton for sale online.

76
00:04:29.625 --> 00:04:31.208
But how are you actually gonna get it?

77
00:04:31.291 --> 00:04:33.500
You've got nothing in the bank
and no clue about boats.

78
00:04:33.583 --> 00:04:35.750
Yeah. that's all true. but how about…

79
00:04:37.125 --> 00:04:38.250
Okay.

80
00:04:39.041 --> 00:04:42.458
I mean. all around the world.
younger generations are coming together

81
00:04:42.541 --> 00:04:44.125
and achieving tremendous things.

82
00:04:44.208 --> 00:04:49.125
I say that we use that same energy
to come up with a creative solution.

83
00:04:49.208 --> 00:04:52.708
Know what I mean? We need
to focus on things greater than ourselves.

84
00:04:52.791 --> 00:04:55.500
If there's a way to save lives.
we should do it.

85
00:05:02.625 --> 00:05:04.041
Hello. Lukas Weiland here.

86
00:05:04.125 --> 00:05:07.958
I saw your boat listed online
and was wondering if I can see it.

87
00:05:08.833 --> 00:05:12.166
I'm a private individual.
I know. It's for a good cause.

88
00:05:12.250 --> 00:05:16.458
I'm… looking for a boat to help migrants
in the Mediterranean in distress.

89
00:05:16.541 --> 00:05:18.000
We're still raising funds.

90
00:05:18.083 --> 00:05:20.166
But I was also curious
about what requirements we need

91
00:05:20.250 --> 00:05:22.041
to meet with these kinds of boats?

92
00:05:22.125 --> 00:05:24.500
Maybe you'd be able to help me with that?

93
00:05:24.583 --> 00:05:28.833
Yeah. I… almost have
all the funding secured. um…

94
00:05:30.083 --> 00:05:31.625
We're getting really close.

95
00:05:32.291 --> 00:05:36.333
Okay. Got it. I'll reach out again
once I have all the money.

96
00:05:36.416 --> 00:05:39.125
You said you wanted me
to have a plan. I've got one.

97
00:05:39.208 --> 00:05:42.000
-Thanks a lot. Lukas. it's wonderful.
-Thank you.

98
00:05:42.083 --> 00:05:46.000
Really. it's great. But in all honesty.
when I said you should have a plan.

99
00:05:46.083 --> 00:05:48.000
I never meant buying a ship.

100
00:05:48.083 --> 00:05:50.083
So. isn't there some other project

101
00:05:50.166 --> 00:05:53.875
between a job at a supermarket
and… some fantasy?

102
00:05:53.958 --> 00:05:56.958
Saving drowning people
isn't exactly my idea of a fantasy.

103
00:05:57.041 --> 00:05:58.750
Oh. come on. I didn't mean it like that.

104
00:05:59.250 --> 00:06:01.166
I can tell you
exactly what's gonna happen.

105
00:06:01.250 --> 00:06:02.500
You'll dive right into this

106
00:06:02.583 --> 00:06:04.666
with all of your passion.
and that's great.

107
00:06:04.750 --> 00:06:06.333
Thing is. you won't raise enough money.

108
00:06:06.416 --> 00:06:09.458
After a year. the only thing you'll have
to show for it is a gap in your resume.

109
00:06:09.541 --> 00:06:12.958
Meanwhile. people like Kitty
will work at human rights law firms

110
00:06:13.041 --> 00:06:14.916
and really advance the cause.

111
00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:17.583
Yeah. well. I'm gonna have
to pass two state exams

112
00:06:17.666 --> 00:06:19.041
before saving the world.

113
00:06:19.125 --> 00:06:20.541
Of course. you'll get it done.

114
00:06:21.583 --> 00:06:23.958
I just don't want to be used
as a kind of counterexample

115
00:06:24.041 --> 00:06:25.750
to criticize your son.

116
00:06:25.833 --> 00:06:27.375
Point taken.

117
00:06:27.458 --> 00:06:29.458
Okay. Forgive me.

118
00:06:29.541 --> 00:06:32.083
The only thing I'm trying to say
is I'm positive

119
00:06:32.166 --> 00:06:35.125
that choosing a conventional path
isn't automatically selfish.

120
00:06:35.208 --> 00:06:36.333
I never said it was.

121
00:06:36.416 --> 00:06:40.083
Okay. say you manage to pull it off
and go down there. then what?

122
00:06:40.166 --> 00:06:42.291
It won't change anything.
The world's not gonna change.

123
00:06:42.375 --> 00:06:44.208
The world <i>must </i>change.

124
00:06:45.625 --> 00:06:47.750
That won't happen if no one does anything.

125
00:06:48.625 --> 00:06:50.500
And how about what your dad thinks?

126
00:06:52.791 --> 00:06:54.541
I don't know. Haven't spoken to him.

127
00:06:54.625 --> 00:06:57.666
I'm just concerned is all. Hmm.

128
00:07:01.875 --> 00:07:03.583
You gotta keep trying.

129
00:07:04.083 --> 00:07:06.750
It's true. Yeah. there's a chance
that your mother's right

130
00:07:06.833 --> 00:07:09.000
and you may not get
the results that you hoped for…

131
00:07:09.083 --> 00:07:10.250
I doubt it though.

132
00:07:10.750 --> 00:07:14.625
And anyway. you can't give up on it now.

133
00:07:15.458 --> 00:07:18.166
You've really gotta try. 'cause you're
convinced it's the right thing.

134
00:07:18.250 --> 00:07:21.208
You can't just be all like.
"Bad idea. Let's just forget about it."

135
00:07:21.291 --> 00:07:24.166
'cause it's too challenging
or it won't look good on your resume.

136
00:07:25.833 --> 00:07:29.958
And I'll be there for you.
Yeah. I will help you as much as possible.

137
00:07:30.041 --> 00:07:31.875
But I'm not dropping out of my studies.

138
00:07:31.958 --> 00:07:34.666
My plan is to get a degree.
and I won't back down.

139
00:07:34.750 --> 00:07:37.500
-I would never ask you to do that.
-I know that. [sighs]

140
00:07:38.916 --> 00:07:41.791
I… I said it as a reminder to myself.

141
00:07:41.875 --> 00:07:44.625
I just know I'll feel guilty
for my choice.

142
00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:52.074
Support us and become VIP member 
to remove all ads from www.OpenSubtitles.org

143
00:07:53.041 --> 00:07:54.416
"Jugend Rettet."

144
00:07:58.000 --> 00:07:59.000
What's that?

145
00:07:59.583 --> 00:08:01.333
"Youth Saves." Your project name.

146
00:08:04.958 --> 00:08:06.958
[both laugh]

147
00:08:09.416 --> 00:08:10.833
{\an8}[energetic music playing]

148
00:08:10.916 --> 00:08:13.125
{\an8}Yeah. this is very impressive.

149
00:08:13.208 --> 00:08:14.833
Great initiative.

150
00:08:14.916 --> 00:08:16.541
-Hmm?
-Mm-hmm.

151
00:08:16.625 --> 00:08:19.375
That's not an easy feat.
Takes a lot of courage.

152
00:08:20.041 --> 00:08:23.875
I'm delighted to see our youth
is starting to get involved in politics.

153
00:08:23.958 --> 00:08:25.375
But this is a bank.

154
00:08:25.458 --> 00:08:27.000
It is <i>not </i>a charity.

155
00:08:28.083 --> 00:08:30.583
Yes. we are a charity.
but we're not a bank.

156
00:08:30.666 --> 00:08:34.416
As a member of parliament.
I'm not a charity or a bank.

157
00:08:34.500 --> 00:08:38.208
And frankly. we all agree
that your project is a little too…

158
00:08:38.708 --> 00:08:40.000
Naive.

159
00:08:40.083 --> 00:08:42.250
I've gotta say. this is quite unrealistic.

160
00:08:42.333 --> 00:08:44.916
Especially coming from someone
as young as you.

161
00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.041
But if you'd like. I'd be happy to put
your name on our internship waitlist.

162
00:08:54.333 --> 00:08:56.625
EVERY PERSON
IN DISTRESS AT SEA DESERVES RESCUE

163
00:08:58.875 --> 00:09:00.333
There are people dying out there

164
00:09:00.416 --> 00:09:02.166
'cause they fled
unbearable living conditions.

165
00:09:02.250 --> 00:09:03.666
And when I say I want to help.

166
00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:07.208
I'm told it's impossible.
it's unrealistic. and naive.

167
00:09:07.833 --> 00:09:11.166
What's actually naive is believing
the problem will solve itself.

168
00:09:11.833 --> 00:09:12.916
Great. thanks.

169
00:09:13.416 --> 00:09:15.041
Can you do the minutes for the session?

170
00:09:15.125 --> 00:09:17.083
-Yeah. sure.
-And here. in case you're interested.

171
00:09:22.666 --> 00:09:24.875
Thanks so much for the photocopies.

172
00:09:24.958 --> 00:09:28.458
No prob.
So you're getting the ship regardless?

173
00:09:28.541 --> 00:09:31.458
I'll find a way to buy it
and reach out for some more funding.

174
00:09:31.541 --> 00:09:33.583
You've gotta shoot for the moon.
am I right?

175
00:09:33.666 --> 00:09:36.000
'Cause you'll still land someplace higher.
Right? Yeah.

176
00:09:36.083 --> 00:09:37.166
-Land anywhere.
-[laughs]

177
00:09:37.250 --> 00:09:39.500
-You got the tape?
-Yeah.

178
00:09:39.583 --> 00:09:41.166
{\an8}[energetic music playing]

179
00:09:41.250 --> 00:09:44.250
{\an8}[Lukas] Every person in distress
at sea deserves rescue.

180
00:09:44.333 --> 00:09:45.375
Everyone deserves rescue.

181
00:09:45.458 --> 00:09:48.500
Hey. we have an information session
Saturday at four on sea rescues.

182
00:09:48.583 --> 00:09:49.875
-Thank you.
-Come by. yeah?

183
00:09:49.958 --> 00:09:54.708
JUGEND RETTET
INFO SESSION

184
00:09:54.791 --> 00:09:58.041
-[girl] Oh. thanks.
-[Lukas] Every person deserves rescue.

185
00:10:00.416 --> 00:10:02.583
[Lukas] <i>Hey there. we're organizing</i>
<i>sea rescue efforts.</i>

186
00:10:02.666 --> 00:10:05.375
<i>Feel free to drop by</i>
<i>on Saturday at 4:00 p.m.</i>

187
00:10:05.458 --> 00:10:08.041
We want to organize sea rescues.
Check out our Facebook page.

188
00:10:08.125 --> 00:10:09.916
-You'll find all the info there.
-Cool.

189
00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:11.541
Our first meeting's Saturday at 4:00.

190
00:10:16.458 --> 00:10:18.208
Here. if you want to get involved.

191
00:10:33.333 --> 00:10:35.333
[energetic music fades]

192
00:10:51.916 --> 00:10:53.625
[reporter] <i>Out at sea.</i>
<i>in the Mediterranean.</i>

193
00:10:53.708 --> 00:10:55.708
<i>hundreds of people are believed</i>
<i>to have died</i>

194
00:10:55.791 --> 00:10:57.875
<i>in one of the worst refugee tragedies.</i>

195
00:10:57.958 --> 00:11:01.833
<i>A trawler with an estimated 700 refugees</i>
<i>on board capsized last night.</i>

196
00:11:01.916 --> 00:11:05.833
<i>between the Libyan coast</i>
<i>and the Italian island of Lampedusa.</i>

197
00:11:05.916 --> 00:11:09.625
<i>According to the UNHCR.</i>
<i>only 28 refugees were rescued.</i>

198
00:11:09.708 --> 00:11:12.958
<i>As a result. the Federal Minister</i>
<i>of the Interior. Thomas de Maizière.</i>

199
00:11:13.041 --> 00:11:15.541
<i>is calling for a strategy</i>
<i>within the European Union</i>

200
00:11:15.625 --> 00:11:19.666
<i>to combat refugee smuggling gangs</i>
<i>to stabilize the region.</i>

201
00:11:22.416 --> 00:11:24.500
[reporter 2] <i>As far as we know.</i>
<i>the boat capsized</i>

202
00:11:24.583 --> 00:11:27.833
<i>most likely because the refugees rushed</i>
<i>to the side of the vessel</i>

203
00:11:27.916 --> 00:11:29.916
<i>the rescuers were arriving at.</i>

204
00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:33.750
<i>There is simply a lack of ships everywhere</i>
<i>to help rescue people.</i>

205
00:11:33.833 --> 00:11:37.791
<i>Aid organizations estimate that</i>
<i>in the first months of this current year.</i>

206
00:11:37.875 --> 00:11:40.250
<i>nearly 1.600 people have perished.</i>

207
00:11:40.333 --> 00:11:42.833
<i>trying to escape from Africa</i>
<i>to get to Italy.</i>

208
00:11:42.916 --> 00:11:44.875
<i>These figures are unprecedented.</i>

209
00:11:44.958 --> 00:11:46.541
[tense music playing]

210
00:11:46.625 --> 00:11:48.958
SHIP

211
00:11:54.041 --> 00:11:58.041
Hey. I'm hanging up your info
to get an overview of where we're at.

212
00:11:59.291 --> 00:12:02.458
Okay. timing-wise. it's already too late
to plan a mission this year.

213
00:12:02.541 --> 00:12:06.000
Our goal is to have a vessel
in the Mediterranean by next summer.

214
00:12:06.083 --> 00:12:07.500
am I right?

215
00:12:07.583 --> 00:12:10.416
So. we've got six months left
to secure a ship.

216
00:12:10.500 --> 00:12:16.333
and we need to get people to help
with PR. logistics. and hiring a crew.

217
00:12:16.833 --> 00:12:18.583
We need financing.

218
00:12:21.208 --> 00:12:22.791
HELPERS - MONEY - SHIP

219
00:12:22.875 --> 00:12:27.625
I know this is gonna sound crazy.
but I'm obsessed with all this.

220
00:12:27.708 --> 00:12:28.666
Like. I lay awake.

221
00:12:28.750 --> 00:12:30.916
Every day. I sit in seminars.
and we keep talking

222
00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.541
about how something has to be done.

223
00:12:33.625 --> 00:12:37.166
And here you are.
actually doing something about the crisis.

224
00:12:37.250 --> 00:12:39.916
I feel like I'm just irrelevant. [sighs]

225
00:12:41.125 --> 00:12:42.375
You all right?

226
00:12:43.958 --> 00:12:45.375
Yeah. no. all good.

227
00:12:45.458 --> 00:12:48.208
Uh. this is great.

228
00:12:50.166 --> 00:12:53.125
-Great.
-So. does that… mean you're in?

229
00:12:53.791 --> 00:12:54.875
-Yeah.
-[chuckles]

230
00:12:54.958 --> 00:12:56.541
Yeah.

231
00:12:56.625 --> 00:13:00.166
So. you take care of the ship.
and I'll handle… logistics and stuff.

232
00:13:00.250 --> 00:13:04.250
recruiting volunteers.
and we'll handle financing together.

233
00:13:04.333 --> 00:13:06.750
-Okay.
-How much money do we need?

234
00:13:06.833 --> 00:13:10.791
Um… so we need
for the boat. fuel. food. accommodations.

235
00:13:10.875 --> 00:13:12.916
medical supplies. life jackets.
and all that.

236
00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:15.250
I'd say 300.000 euros.

237
00:13:16.458 --> 00:13:17.666
300.000?

238
00:13:18.250 --> 00:13:21.166
[sighs] Yeah. 'cause ships go
for 60.000 to 100.000.

239
00:13:22.041 --> 00:13:23.041
[sighs]

240
00:13:23.541 --> 00:13:25.666
So. any idea how we're gonna finance that?

241
00:13:25.750 --> 00:13:28.208
Sorta. I thought about some crowd funding.

242
00:13:28.291 --> 00:13:32.916
Charity… donations. and… a flea market.

243
00:13:33.833 --> 00:13:37.083
-A flea market?
-Yeah. we can sell clothes and stuff.

244
00:13:37.166 --> 00:13:38.291
Mm-hmm.

245
00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:40.791
[energetic music playing]

246
00:13:44.208 --> 00:13:47.208
{\an8}20-WEEK CROWDFUNDING CAMPAIGN:

247
00:13:47.291 --> 00:13:49.375
{\an8}GOAL: 300.000 EUROS

248
00:13:50.041 --> 00:13:51.458
-May I?
-Sure.

249
00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.541
{\an8}-Thanks a lot. Bye.
-Every donation helps!

250
00:13:55.625 --> 00:13:56.875
{\an8}WEEK 1

251
00:13:56.958 --> 00:13:59.916
-How much have we raised?
-Uh… around 300?

252
00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.458
Great. only 299.700 left.

253
00:14:02.541 --> 00:14:04.625
-Hey! Hello. [giggles]
-Oh. just that! Hey. Domi!

254
00:14:04.708 --> 00:14:06.208
How's it going? [chuckles]

255
00:14:06.291 --> 00:14:09.208
Guys. this is Dominique.
She's gonna be in charge of our PR.

256
00:14:09.291 --> 00:14:10.458
-[Kitty] Awesome.
-Hey.

257
00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:15.875
Here's a logo in another mock-up.

258
00:14:15.958 --> 00:14:17.666
Okay. that one's real powerful.

259
00:14:17.750 --> 00:14:19.625
-That's not it.
-Why don't you like it?

260
00:14:19.708 --> 00:14:21.833
'Cause the message is all wrong
with the fist.

261
00:14:21.916 --> 00:14:23.500
{\an8}WEEK 4

262
00:14:24.625 --> 00:14:25.666
[squeaks]

263
00:14:26.416 --> 00:14:29.875
This one's my absolute favorite.
It's Kitty's artwork.

264
00:14:29.958 --> 00:14:31.208
Yeah. I think it's great.

265
00:14:31.291 --> 00:14:32.416
[Domi chuckles]

266
00:14:32.500 --> 00:14:35.125
{\an8}WEEK 6

267
00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.625
[chuckles] Go on. open 'em!

268
00:14:44.708 --> 00:14:48.541
We were just trying to get some actors
to post about us on their socials.

269
00:14:48.625 --> 00:14:50.708
[woman] <i>So we contacted</i>
<i>the German Film Academy.</i>

270
00:14:50.791 --> 00:14:52.250
<i>and they loved our idea.</i>

271
00:14:52.333 --> 00:14:54.500
<i>They had an available office.</i>
<i>and they offered it to us.</i>

272
00:14:55.250 --> 00:14:57.666
-Hey! So you're Lukas?
-Hi. Yeah. that's me.

273
00:14:57.750 --> 00:15:00.041
-Hi. I'm Katja. Pleased to meet you.
-So nice to meet you.

274
00:15:00.125 --> 00:15:02.000
Thanks. What you're doing is great. Bravo.

275
00:15:02.083 --> 00:15:04.500
{\an8}WEEK 8

276
00:15:05.416 --> 00:15:07.416
[man on PA] <i>Connections available to…</i>

277
00:15:07.500 --> 00:15:10.041
Nina? Lukas? Check this out. Finished it.

278
00:15:10.916 --> 00:15:12.333
-[gasps]
-Nice!

279
00:15:12.416 --> 00:15:13.791
It came together well. didn't it?

280
00:15:13.875 --> 00:15:16.041
[Domi] You're our hero!
Hell yeah. we have a website!

281
00:15:16.125 --> 00:15:19.291
-I'm Domi. Thanks for coming.
-Hi. I'm Sam. I'm glad to be here.

282
00:15:19.375 --> 00:15:22.166
-Happy you're here. I'm Domi.
-Hey. Hi. I'm Paula. How are you doing?

283
00:15:22.250 --> 00:15:24.541
{\an8}[Katja on video] <i>Jugend Rettet</i>
<i>is committed to our moral</i>

284
00:15:24.625 --> 00:15:27.750
{\an8}<i>and legal obligation to rescue people</i>
<i>from drowning.</i>

285
00:15:27.833 --> 00:15:31.458
{\an8}<i>In order to accomplish that.</i>
<i>the team needs a ship.</i>

286
00:15:31.541 --> 00:15:34.291
{\an8}<i>So we're calling on you for donations.</i>

287
00:15:34.375 --> 00:15:36.375
{\an8}The train ride took over ten hours
to get here!

288
00:15:36.458 --> 00:15:38.250
{\an8}How can they not even show up?

289
00:15:41.791 --> 00:15:43.375
[sighs deeply]

290
00:15:43.875 --> 00:15:45.791
[Nina] We're gonna have
to choose one soon.

291
00:15:45.875 --> 00:15:47.166
Because if we don't target one.

292
00:15:47.250 --> 00:15:50.541
we won't get to show our donors the ship
we want. and crowdfunding will tank.

293
00:15:50.625 --> 00:15:52.875
People need to know
what they're encouraging.

294
00:15:52.958 --> 00:15:55.333
-I know.
-[Nina] Without any money. no ship.

295
00:15:55.416 --> 00:15:56.708
And that's it for our project.

296
00:15:56.791 --> 00:15:58.333
We can donate money and call it quits!

297
00:15:58.416 --> 00:16:00.000
I get it. Nina. all right?

298
00:16:04.708 --> 00:16:10.000
{\an8}WEEK 18: 121.000 EUROS RAISED

299
00:16:28.083 --> 00:16:31.666
-[chuckles]
-How about loyalty points? [laughs]

300
00:16:32.875 --> 00:16:35.750
-[Lukas] No! No! No way!
-Yes! Yes! I knew you'd get it!

301
00:16:35.833 --> 00:16:38.208
-God! I've got to get it.
-This street!

302
00:16:38.291 --> 00:16:40.166
-The bank is loving this.
-How can I pay for it?

303
00:16:40.250 --> 00:16:42.916
-Okay. It costs thousands!
-Wait. What do I have? A hotel?

304
00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:45.500
-It still costs…
-I'm gonna need to get a mortgage on it.

305
00:16:45.583 --> 00:16:47.166
-[phone vibrating]
-Oh. just a sec.

306
00:16:47.250 --> 00:16:50.625
-19.000.
-Just a minute. Yes? Hello?

307
00:16:50.708 --> 00:16:53.083
"Zoning change approved.
Collect 50 dollars per property…"

308
00:16:53.166 --> 00:16:55.166
I thought it wasn't available anymore.

309
00:16:56.833 --> 00:17:00.416
Uh. no. no. We don't have a ship.
We're still looking.

310
00:17:01.458 --> 00:17:02.458
Yeah.

311
00:17:03.208 --> 00:17:06.333
Okay. then. How about I call you
from the office tomorrow?

312
00:17:07.291 --> 00:17:08.791
Great. thanks a lot. Cheers.

313
00:17:10.708 --> 00:17:11.708
We got one.

314
00:17:13.333 --> 00:17:14.958
[exclaims. laughs]

315
00:17:15.041 --> 00:17:16.250
Guess what?

316
00:17:18.333 --> 00:17:19.416
I found us a ship.

317
00:17:19.500 --> 00:17:21.875
-[gasps] You did?
-Yeah. I saw it on one of my trips.

318
00:17:21.958 --> 00:17:23.125
But it wasn't available.

319
00:17:24.166 --> 00:17:25.916
But it turns out it is after all.

320
00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.750
-[Nina] Okay.
-Scooch! [grunts]

321
00:17:29.250 --> 00:17:34.125
The Alk Explorer was a patrol boat
in the North Sea.

322
00:17:34.208 --> 00:17:36.875
So it doubles as a hospital.
the engine's totally overhauled.

323
00:17:36.958 --> 00:17:39.333
Plus. there's room
for over 200 people on deck.

324
00:17:39.416 --> 00:17:41.375
And I think the most crucial detail.
what's great.

325
00:17:41.458 --> 00:17:44.500
is it's got a lower entry point.
so it's easier to get people on board.

326
00:17:44.583 --> 00:17:47.041
Mm-hmm. And what's the catch?

327
00:17:48.291 --> 00:17:50.541
Uh. it costs 150.000.

328
00:17:52.083 --> 00:17:54.500
-Yeah. great.
-[Mauro sighs]

329
00:17:54.583 --> 00:17:57.833
The deadline for our crowdfunding
is two weeks from now.

330
00:17:57.916 --> 00:18:02.083
We don't have a ship quite yet.
Unfortunately. we can't afford it.

331
00:18:02.166 --> 00:18:05.125
As it stands. we're gonna miss
our campaign goal. sadly.

332
00:18:05.208 --> 00:18:07.166
By quite a lot. Almost half.

333
00:18:08.125 --> 00:18:10.041
Anyone have other ideas?

334
00:18:10.958 --> 00:18:12.208
Well. all hope's not gone yet.

335
00:18:12.291 --> 00:18:15.083
It seems two parties
are still considering larger donations.

336
00:18:15.791 --> 00:18:21.750
Um. one of them… is a start-up
for e-cigarettes. Drag & Joy.

337
00:18:21.833 --> 00:18:24.250
They're thinking of giving an extra 20.000

338
00:18:24.333 --> 00:18:26.958
provided that we print their slogan
on the life jackets.

339
00:18:27.041 --> 00:18:28.791
What exactly is their slogan?

340
00:18:28.875 --> 00:18:30.708
"A new source of pleasure."

341
00:18:30.791 --> 00:18:31.791
[chuckles]

342
00:18:31.875 --> 00:18:33.791
[Nina] So 100 people
will be sitting in a dinghy

343
00:18:33.875 --> 00:18:36.000
with life jackets that say.
"A new source of pleasure."

344
00:18:36.083 --> 00:18:37.750
-[chuckles]
-Holy moly…

345
00:18:37.833 --> 00:18:40.250
And what is the second option?

346
00:18:40.750 --> 00:18:44.458
Um. it's a married couple
with a private foundation.

347
00:18:44.958 --> 00:18:46.958
[indistinct chatter]

348
00:18:50.041 --> 00:18:51.125
-Here?
-[Nina] Yes.

349
00:18:53.666 --> 00:18:56.625
[woman] <i>We only promote</i>
<i>non-profit projects run by people</i>

350
00:18:56.708 --> 00:18:59.916
who are truly committed to actively
and democratically participating

351
00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:03.041
in shaping their living environments.

352
00:19:03.125 --> 00:19:06.458
In that sense. Jugend Rettet
really caught our attention.

353
00:19:07.583 --> 00:19:10.083
That's why we asked you to come here.

354
00:19:10.166 --> 00:19:12.416
We'd like to hear more
about how you wish to do this.

355
00:19:13.958 --> 00:19:14.958
-[sighs]
-Go ahead.

356
00:19:15.041 --> 00:19:17.875
-Well. in the package we prepared--
-Who can tell me about the numbers?

357
00:19:22.291 --> 00:19:23.375
I can answer Oh. go on.

358
00:19:23.458 --> 00:19:24.708
And what are your majors?

359
00:19:25.208 --> 00:19:29.625
-Uh. social and economic communication.
-[sighs] International relations.

360
00:19:29.708 --> 00:19:32.208
And I'm still finding my way. sir.

361
00:19:32.291 --> 00:19:36.083
Have you got anyone with actual experience
in the field working with you?

362
00:19:36.166 --> 00:19:37.875
Currently. no. but we're busy looking.

363
00:19:37.958 --> 00:19:41.500
Do you have anyone with
a financial background to manage funds?

364
00:19:41.583 --> 00:19:42.916
We're in the process of that.

365
00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:44.458
-[man] A lawyer?
-We have a team.

366
00:19:44.541 --> 00:19:47.583
Or someone who's done more
than just start an undergrad degree.

367
00:19:47.666 --> 00:19:50.208
or is everyone just… "finding their way"?

368
00:19:50.291 --> 00:19:53.000
You're absolutely right.
We're not professionals.

369
00:19:53.583 --> 00:19:55.750
Nobody on our team has a degree yet.

370
00:19:55.833 --> 00:19:57.375
We're all just getting started.

371
00:19:57.458 --> 00:19:59.625
But I assure you that we are serious.

372
00:19:59.708 --> 00:20:02.041
We'll make up for our innocence
with passion.

373
00:20:02.125 --> 00:20:05.041
That's exactly why we're looking
for experienced people like you

374
00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.208
who share our commitment to humanity.

375
00:20:08.958 --> 00:20:10.625
So. nobody.

376
00:20:18.541 --> 00:20:20.041
[Domi sighs]

377
00:20:23.166 --> 00:20:24.666
We need a plan B.

378
00:20:25.666 --> 00:20:27.958
How about we downsize a little?

379
00:20:28.458 --> 00:20:32.666
Get a smaller ship. postpone
the start date. and do fewer missions.

380
00:20:34.166 --> 00:20:37.416
There's a smaller ship we could look into…

381
00:20:37.500 --> 00:20:38.500
The Passat.

382
00:20:38.583 --> 00:20:41.083
I'm familiar with it.
I went to check it out.

383
00:20:41.166 --> 00:20:42.416
Yeah? That's great.

384
00:20:42.500 --> 00:20:46.833
At least you know… the ship. [sighs]

385
00:20:46.916 --> 00:20:47.958
[Lukas] Shit.

386
00:20:52.583 --> 00:20:54.583
[cell phone ringing]

387
00:20:58.625 --> 00:20:59.625
Yeah?

388
00:21:02.250 --> 00:21:03.416
Uh. okay.

389
00:21:04.125 --> 00:21:05.041
Mm-hmm.

390
00:21:05.583 --> 00:21:07.333
Yes. great. Very well.

391
00:21:08.208 --> 00:21:09.333
Lukas!

392
00:21:12.791 --> 00:21:13.791
[knocking on door]

393
00:21:22.208 --> 00:21:23.333
Okay.

394
00:21:25.500 --> 00:21:27.166
[line ringing]

395
00:21:27.250 --> 00:21:28.333
[woman on phone] <i>Hello?</i>

396
00:21:28.416 --> 00:21:30.916
-Mrs. Gans? Hello. we're all here.
<i>-Good.</i>

397
00:21:31.958 --> 00:21:35.958
Uh. we took a closer look at the budget.
and we think it's quite reasonable.

398
00:21:36.041 --> 00:21:39.250
-Ask her about the office. The office.
-Right.

399
00:21:39.333 --> 00:21:43.583
The thing is. we noticed a few items
were missing from your calculations.

400
00:21:43.666 --> 00:21:46.791
For example. how much your office costs.

401
00:21:46.875 --> 00:21:48.958
It's sponsored by the German Film Academy.

402
00:21:49.041 --> 00:21:50.416
<i>Aha. okay.</i>

403
00:21:50.500 --> 00:21:53.208
And the cost of the shipyard
for prepping the ship?

404
00:21:53.291 --> 00:21:55.500
The owner of the shipyard
has waived the costs.

405
00:21:55.583 --> 00:21:58.291
He wants to give back.
Plus. it's an easy tax write-off.

406
00:21:59.333 --> 00:22:01.458
Good. Accommodations in Malta?

407
00:22:01.541 --> 00:22:04.000
Uh. we'll use an old lighthouse.

408
00:22:04.083 --> 00:22:06.208
Let me guess. it's also been sponsored?

409
00:22:06.291 --> 00:22:08.208
-Correct. Yes.
-Yeah.

410
00:22:09.125 --> 00:22:11.708
I have to say. though. that we do have
concerns on our end

411
00:22:11.791 --> 00:22:13.333
<i>about the expertise in your project</i>

412
00:22:13.416 --> 00:22:15.333
<i>and about the structure</i>
<i>of the organization.</i>

413
00:22:15.416 --> 00:22:19.666
We're also wondering how
you'll finance missions in the long-term.

414
00:22:21.583 --> 00:22:23.375
We'll buy your ship. though.

415
00:22:26.291 --> 00:22:27.583
-What?
<i>-Yeah.</i>

416
00:22:28.625 --> 00:22:32.333
<i>My husband and I have agreed</i>
<i>to buy the ship for you.</i>

417
00:22:32.833 --> 00:22:37.125
-[group exclaims]
-[gasps] Yes! Yes!

418
00:22:37.916 --> 00:22:40.833
<i>-Have a nice evening.</i>
-You too. Thanks so much.

419
00:22:40.916 --> 00:22:42.833
[all exclaim]

420
00:22:42.916 --> 00:22:44.708
[reporter] <i>As an individual.</i>
<i>one is powerless</i>

421
00:22:44.791 --> 00:22:46.875
<i>and cannot change the world.</i>

422
00:22:46.958 --> 00:22:52.000
<i>Well. a few students here in Berlin</i>
<i>make a point against that worldview.</i>

423
00:22:52.083 --> 00:22:54.750
<i>In the factory hall in the port of Emden</i>
<i>lies a ship.</i>

424
00:22:54.833 --> 00:22:58.041
<i>bought by the Jugend Rettet organization.</i>
<i>a group of young people</i>

425
00:22:58.125 --> 00:23:01.375
<i>who stand by their convictions</i>
<i>and want to venture into the Mediterranean</i>

426
00:23:01.458 --> 00:23:04.583
<i>in just four weeks to rescue refugees</i>
<i>in distress at sea.</i>

427
00:23:04.666 --> 00:23:06.958
<i>They've been renovating</i>
<i>the ship themselves</i>

428
00:23:07.041 --> 00:23:08.250
<i>for the past two months</i>

429
00:23:08.333 --> 00:23:12.041
<i>and their profound commitment has been</i>
<i>pulling at the heartstrings of the nation.</i>

430
00:23:12.125 --> 00:23:12.958
[man] Okay.

431
00:23:13.041 --> 00:23:16.208
We saw on Facebook that an awesome group
of young people were having issues

432
00:23:16.291 --> 00:23:18.750
with the electrical stuff.
so we're helping out

433
00:23:18.833 --> 00:23:20.000
It's for a good cause.

434
00:23:20.083 --> 00:23:21.708
[reporter] <i>And after all that hard work.</i>

435
00:23:21.791 --> 00:23:24.291
<i>the Iuventa is finally ready to set off</i>
<i>for Malta.</i>

436
00:23:24.375 --> 00:23:26.000
<i>Today's a big day for the mission.</i>

437
00:23:26.083 --> 00:23:28.958
[together] We hereby christen you Iuventa.

438
00:23:29.041 --> 00:23:31.541
<i>-Jugend!</i>
<i>-Jugend! Jugend!</i>

439
00:23:31.625 --> 00:23:34.708
[crowd cheers]

440
00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:44.000
{\an8}MALTA. JULY 2016

441
00:23:47.666 --> 00:23:49.458
[man] All right. Watch your heads.

442
00:23:49.541 --> 00:23:51.416
Hey. watch your head.

443
00:23:51.500 --> 00:23:54.583
All right. slow down. Down there.

444
00:23:54.666 --> 00:23:56.958
Hey. um… I'm Maik.

445
00:23:57.041 --> 00:24:01.208
Uh. I just finished high school.
And. uh. I'm glad I got my diploma.

446
00:24:01.291 --> 00:24:04.166
But I guess that what matters more to me
than pursuing my studies

447
00:24:04.250 --> 00:24:05.583
is saving people's lives.

448
00:24:05.666 --> 00:24:07.375
That's why it's really
such a massive honor

449
00:24:07.458 --> 00:24:08.541
to be here with you.

450
00:24:08.625 --> 00:24:11.041
Plus. you're all really cool. Thank you.

451
00:24:11.666 --> 00:24:13.250
-Next one!
-[grunts]

452
00:24:13.333 --> 00:24:15.083
[Paula] <i>Hi. My name's Paula.</i>

453
00:24:15.166 --> 00:24:19.291
I read on Facebook that you're looking
for someone who's fluent in Arabic.

454
00:24:19.375 --> 00:24:22.333
Well. I'm studying it.
and I think we need to be the change.

455
00:24:22.416 --> 00:24:23.500
Action is hope. right?

456
00:24:23.583 --> 00:24:27.041
[man] <i>Good. Hey. I'm Sören.</i>
<i>the head of mission on board.</i>

457
00:24:27.125 --> 00:24:30.208
Gotta say. it feels a bit strange
that I'm the oldest one here.

458
00:24:30.291 --> 00:24:32.041
Before you contacted me.

459
00:24:32.125 --> 00:24:35.541
I was working on the Sea-Watch
and before that. on the Lesbos.

460
00:24:35.625 --> 00:24:38.833
I hope I can be of service to you
with my experience.

461
00:24:38.916 --> 00:24:41.458
I'm Viola. the captain.

462
00:24:41.541 --> 00:24:44.291
And. um. I was with Sören
on the Sea-Watch.

463
00:24:44.375 --> 00:24:48.625
My main source of income has been pushing
a 5.000-ton walker over the sea.

464
00:24:48.708 --> 00:24:50.708
I'm first officer
on a seniors' cruise ship.

465
00:24:50.791 --> 00:24:54.291
The thing is. I believe we can't just wish
for a just world and talk about it.

466
00:24:54.375 --> 00:24:57.000
You have to want to put those words
into action.

467
00:24:57.083 --> 00:24:58.625
-[woman] Hey!
-Oh! Hey!

468
00:24:58.708 --> 00:24:59.958
-Ah. Su!
-Hey. sorry I'm late.

469
00:25:00.041 --> 00:25:02.458
We're just doing the introduction round.
It's perfect timing.

470
00:25:02.541 --> 00:25:04.708
-Shoot!
-Oh. okay. Uh…

471
00:25:04.791 --> 00:25:08.375
Cool. Uh. so. I'm Su.

472
00:25:08.458 --> 00:25:10.583
I. uh. sorry I missed some introductions.

473
00:25:10.666 --> 00:25:12.416
Looking forward
to getting to know you all.

474
00:25:12.500 --> 00:25:15.833
Next year. I'm starting a residency
as an orthopedist.

475
00:25:15.916 --> 00:25:19.458
And meanwhile. I will serve
as an onboard doctor on the Iuventa.

476
00:25:19.541 --> 00:25:21.541
[hopeful music rises]

477
00:25:23.250 --> 00:25:25.625
Bye! Take care of yourselves!

478
00:25:29.041 --> 00:25:30.666
[Nina] You've got this!

479
00:25:32.333 --> 00:25:34.791
-Well. at least the engine's working.
-Yeah.

480
00:25:34.875 --> 00:25:37.916
It's ancient. but on the flip side.
it was free.

481
00:25:38.916 --> 00:25:40.541
[laughs]

482
00:25:41.291 --> 00:25:43.750
FIRST MISSION 2016
JULY 24

483
00:25:43.833 --> 00:25:46.250
DAY 1: 198 NAUTICAL MILES OFF LIBYA

484
00:25:46.333 --> 00:25:50.750
The sooner we start compression
and ventilation. the better the outcome.

485
00:25:50.833 --> 00:25:54.083
And you have to keep going
until he opens his eyes.

486
00:25:54.166 --> 00:25:56.833
Okay? So you press
and you give him ventilation.

487
00:25:56.916 --> 00:25:57.916
-Yeah.
-Okay.

488
00:25:58.500 --> 00:26:02.375
All right. One. two. three. One. two…

489
00:26:02.458 --> 00:26:04.541
-[coughing]
-You're pressing on his stomach.

490
00:26:04.625 --> 00:26:06.750
-Oh…
-So glad I didn't have breakfast.

491
00:26:06.833 --> 00:26:07.916
[group laughs]

492
00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:09.875
And you also have to remove
his T-shirt first.

493
00:26:09.958 --> 00:26:13.083
-Yeah. right. I. uh… Like this. right?
-Yup.

494
00:26:13.166 --> 00:26:17.458
-[sighs] Okay. [chuckles]
-[softly] 'Kay.

495
00:26:17.541 --> 00:26:20.000
-One. two. three. four. five--
-From 20. please.

496
00:26:20.083 --> 00:26:23.375
Uh… 27. 28. 29. 30. Go!

497
00:26:24.125 --> 00:26:26.291
[chuckles]

498
00:26:27.291 --> 00:26:29.291
-Come here. come here.
-[group chuckles]

499
00:26:29.375 --> 00:26:31.750
-[coughing]
-[group laughs]

500
00:26:31.833 --> 00:26:33.708
Come on. it wasn't that bad!

501
00:26:33.791 --> 00:26:35.041
[bright music playing]

502
00:26:35.125 --> 00:26:38.500
So you see. you've also got compasses
in there. for bearings.

503
00:26:38.583 --> 00:26:40.750
Notice anything off?
Quickly tell the bridge.

504
00:26:40.833 --> 00:26:43.166
Lukas. how many degrees there?

505
00:26:43.666 --> 00:26:46.791
[Lukas] Uh… 85.

506
00:26:46.875 --> 00:26:49.500
That's correct.
Then you say. "Boat at 85 degrees."

507
00:26:49.583 --> 00:26:51.458
while you point
your hand towards it. yeah?

508
00:26:51.541 --> 00:26:54.875
You have to keep your finger directly
on it from that point forward. okay?

509
00:26:54.958 --> 00:26:56.875
-[man] Understood.
-Yeah?

510
00:26:56.958 --> 00:26:59.208
And what are rescue missions like for you?

511
00:26:59.291 --> 00:27:02.125
It's never the same. actually.
It's always different.

512
00:27:02.208 --> 00:27:04.708
But. I mean. they must affect you. right?

513
00:27:04.791 --> 00:27:08.583
I'm definitely not more optimistic.
to put it optimistically. I guess.

514
00:27:09.458 --> 00:27:11.375
Yeah. it gets to absolutely everyone.

515
00:27:11.458 --> 00:27:13.875
You're not the same person after.

516
00:27:15.250 --> 00:27:17.250
[bright music building]

517
00:27:19.791 --> 00:27:21.333
[Sören] <i>Let's go down first.</i>

518
00:27:21.416 --> 00:27:23.375
Now. up. Up. up. up!

519
00:27:23.458 --> 00:27:25.958
Yeah. that's good.
Always keep it nice and taut. like this.

520
00:27:26.041 --> 00:27:30.083
Always keep that rope taut.
or you're gonna end up overboard.

521
00:27:30.166 --> 00:27:33.291
You'll fly right off. You'll go swimming.
Okay. please stop.

522
00:27:35.208 --> 00:27:37.875
All right. Try to save me now.

523
00:27:37.958 --> 00:27:40.000
Help! Help!

524
00:27:40.083 --> 00:27:41.458
Help!

525
00:27:42.166 --> 00:27:43.583
Help. help!

526
00:27:44.250 --> 00:27:45.958
Help! Help!

527
00:27:54.208 --> 00:27:55.958
[Lukas gasping]

528
00:27:56.041 --> 00:27:59.250
Okay. okay. Never do what Lukas just did.

529
00:27:59.333 --> 00:28:01.000
Always go against your instincts.

530
00:28:01.083 --> 00:28:03.958
Throw a life jacket in the water
so the person can cling to it. understood?

531
00:28:04.041 --> 00:28:05.458
[group] Yes.

532
00:28:05.541 --> 00:28:08.458
Tomorrow we'll get
to the 24-mile zone off Libya.

533
00:28:08.541 --> 00:28:09.708
This is it. guys.

534
00:28:09.791 --> 00:28:14.000
We could encounter rubber dinghies
transporting refugees at any time.

535
00:28:14.083 --> 00:28:16.125
Passengers are usually traumatized

536
00:28:16.208 --> 00:28:17.833
'cause they've been sitting there
for days.

537
00:28:17.916 --> 00:28:20.041
fighting for their lives
every single minute.

538
00:28:20.125 --> 00:28:23.791
Please know that there isn't
a single usual behavior to expect.

539
00:28:23.875 --> 00:28:24.708
Absolutely.

540
00:28:24.791 --> 00:28:26.541
When there's a rubber dinghy.

541
00:28:26.625 --> 00:28:29.958
engine fishermen are usually lurking
and waiting in the area.

542
00:28:30.041 --> 00:28:32.958
They get the engines back.
Soon as they get the chance.

543
00:28:33.041 --> 00:28:34.833
they dismantle them
and take off with them.

544
00:28:34.916 --> 00:28:37.666
If we do cross paths with them.
just focus on the rescue.

545
00:28:37.791 --> 00:28:39.750
We get everyone off.
we try to destroy the dinghy.

546
00:28:39.833 --> 00:28:43.708
but not if it puts our safety.
or the people we're rescuing. at risk.

547
00:28:43.791 --> 00:28:46.791
[Sören] Moving on.
This is the so-called Libyan coast guard.

548
00:28:46.875 --> 00:28:49.625
They're… actually Libyan militia.

549
00:28:49.708 --> 00:28:51.875
And they're mostly young guys

550
00:28:51.958 --> 00:28:56.041
who've just fought in the civil war
and organize the escape boats.

551
00:28:56.125 --> 00:28:57.291
Armed. as you can see.

552
00:28:57.375 --> 00:28:59.500
They're aggressive and up for a fight.

553
00:28:59.583 --> 00:29:01.125
These guys are dangerous.

554
00:29:01.208 --> 00:29:02.666
Be super careful.

555
00:29:13.083 --> 00:29:17.625
[Lukas] <i>Hey.</i>
<i>I'm doing night watch tonight.</i>

556
00:29:18.833 --> 00:29:21.666
<i>It's so crazy. The sea's totally calm.</i>

557
00:29:21.750 --> 00:29:23.666
<i>It's pitch black.</i>

558
00:29:23.750 --> 00:29:25.500
<i>What are you up to?</i>

559
00:29:27.708 --> 00:29:30.625
[Kitty] <i>I've gotta work today.</i>
<i>How are you guys?</i>

560
00:29:33.166 --> 00:29:34.375
[Lukas] <i>Pretty good.</i>

561
00:29:35.625 --> 00:29:39.375
<i>When we were starting all this</i>
<i>in Berlin. then renovating the ship.</i>

562
00:29:39.458 --> 00:29:41.333
<i>everything seemed so clear.</i>

563
00:29:41.416 --> 00:29:43.541
<i>We didn't question anything.</i>

564
00:29:44.375 --> 00:29:46.791
<i>But out here.</i>
<i>it feels completely different.</i>

565
00:29:47.958 --> 00:29:49.875
<i>Suddenly it all seems so real.</i>

566
00:29:53.250 --> 00:29:56.500
<i>We're really scared…</i>
<i>of messing up. you know?</i>

567
00:30:02.041 --> 00:30:03.625
[Kitty] <i>I totally get that.</i>

568
00:30:05.250 --> 00:30:07.083
<i>But you can count on each other.</i>

569
00:30:07.625 --> 00:30:09.541
<i>Together is always better.</i>

570
00:30:15.375 --> 00:30:16.625
[Lukas] <i>I miss you.</i>

571
00:30:20.500 --> 00:30:23.041
[Kitty] <i>I miss you too. A lot.</i>

572
00:30:30.125 --> 00:30:35.250
FIRST MISSION 2016. 26 JULY. 5:23 A.M.
18 NAUTICAL MILES OFF THE COAST OF LIBYA

573
00:30:59.250 --> 00:31:01.125
[gasps] Bridge to lookout.

574
00:31:01.208 --> 00:31:03.083
[Viola] <i>Lookout to Bridge. receiving.</i>

575
00:31:03.166 --> 00:31:04.958
I see a boat. ten o'clock.

576
00:31:05.041 --> 00:31:07.041
[suspenseful music rises]

577
00:31:13.208 --> 00:31:14.875
Lukas. we're on. Let's go.

578
00:31:16.125 --> 00:31:19.083
Let's go. Good morning MRCC.
this is motor vessel Iuventa.

579
00:31:19.166 --> 00:31:23.458
I'm in position 33 degrees.
22.2 minutes north

580
00:31:23.541 --> 00:31:27.375
<i>and 012 degrees. 21. 8 minutes east.</i>

581
00:31:27.458 --> 00:31:31.291
I've spotted a boat in distress.
three miles south of our position.

582
00:31:38.750 --> 00:31:41.500
Pull it up. Up. up. up. up.

583
00:31:42.166 --> 00:31:43.500
Now we go out.

584
00:31:43.583 --> 00:31:45.375
Out. out. out. out.

585
00:31:45.458 --> 00:31:47.541
Slowly. slowly. slowly. slowly.

586
00:31:52.916 --> 00:31:55.333
-Okay.
-There they are. Call it in.

587
00:31:55.416 --> 00:31:57.208
Iuventa. Iuventa. Iuventa. RHIB.

588
00:31:57.291 --> 00:31:58.666
Iuventa. RHIB. Iuventa.

589
00:31:58.750 --> 00:32:00.791
<i>Got a visual of the boat.</i>
<i>likely a rubber dinghy.</i>

590
00:32:00.875 --> 00:32:03.916
Head count is unclear. We're approaching.

591
00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:05.541
Copy. standing by.

592
00:32:21.666 --> 00:32:23.208
Slow down.

593
00:32:23.291 --> 00:32:25.291
[passengers calling out]

594
00:32:27.541 --> 00:32:28.916
Hello!

595
00:32:30.041 --> 00:32:31.416
Hello!

596
00:32:31.916 --> 00:32:34.708
We are from a European rescue vessel.

597
00:32:35.875 --> 00:32:36.875
Hello!

598
00:32:37.916 --> 00:32:39.375
We're here to help you.

599
00:32:40.375 --> 00:32:42.125
You're safe now.

600
00:32:42.916 --> 00:32:44.875
Calm down. you're safe now.

601
00:32:44.958 --> 00:32:47.250
We've come to help you.

602
00:32:47.333 --> 00:32:49.833
Is every… Is everything good?
Are you good?

603
00:32:50.833 --> 00:32:52.833
Is… is everyone all right?

604
00:32:52.916 --> 00:32:54.916
We'll come to you. okay?

605
00:32:56.166 --> 00:32:58.750
-Do you speak English?
-Yes.

606
00:32:58.833 --> 00:33:00.333
-What's your name?
-Lamin.

607
00:33:00.416 --> 00:33:02.125
[Lukas] Lamin? My name is Lukas.

608
00:33:02.208 --> 00:33:04.958
That's Mauro and that's Wanda.
We're gonna do this together now.

609
00:33:05.041 --> 00:33:06.375
-Okay?
-Yes.

610
00:33:06.458 --> 00:33:08.041
-Is anyone injured?
-No.

611
00:33:08.125 --> 00:33:09.791
How many women and children are on board?

612
00:33:10.875 --> 00:33:12.666
Six women and one baby.

613
00:33:12.750 --> 00:33:15.666
-Six women and one baby.
-There are six women and a baby on board.

614
00:33:15.750 --> 00:33:17.583
These are life vests.

615
00:33:17.666 --> 00:33:19.666
You put them over your head.

616
00:33:20.375 --> 00:33:24.291
then strap around
and make them really tight. Okay?

617
00:33:24.375 --> 00:33:26.833
We're gonna start handing them out now.

618
00:33:28.291 --> 00:33:30.291
-Okay?
-There you go.

619
00:33:30.375 --> 00:33:32.583
-Wait. wait. wait!
-No. wait!

620
00:33:32.666 --> 00:33:34.875
-No fighting. please!
-[clamoring]

621
00:33:34.958 --> 00:33:37.958
We've got enough for everyone!
No fighting. please!

622
00:33:38.041 --> 00:33:40.125
-Let's pass them on to the back.
-Wait. stop!

623
00:33:40.208 --> 00:33:43.416
Please. pass them on to the back.
Hand them down. please.

624
00:33:43.500 --> 00:33:45.916
Hand them down. Hand them down. Lamin.

625
00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:48.083
-Pass them to the back!
-No fighting!

626
00:33:48.166 --> 00:33:51.041
-[Lukas] There's enough for everyone.
-[shouting]

627
00:33:51.125 --> 00:33:53.625
[Lukas] Please hand them down.
hand them down.

628
00:33:53.708 --> 00:33:55.708
[clamoring]

629
00:34:03.166 --> 00:34:05.083
[Sören] Okay? Welcome on board.

630
00:34:05.166 --> 00:34:07.416
[Su] Hi. welcome on board.
Be careful. be careful!

631
00:34:07.500 --> 00:34:09.791
-[Sören] Welcome. You're doing good.
-[Su] Watch your step.

632
00:34:09.875 --> 00:34:12.916
Okay. slowly. slowly. Nice.

633
00:34:13.666 --> 00:34:16.208
[clamoring]

634
00:34:16.291 --> 00:34:18.458
Welcome. welcome.

635
00:34:19.750 --> 00:34:22.166
-Hi. I'll help you.
-Okay. slowly. slowly.

636
00:34:22.250 --> 00:34:25.125
Are you okay? I'm the doctor. okay?
You can tell me whatever you need.

637
00:34:26.791 --> 00:34:29.000
[excited chatter]

638
00:34:30.041 --> 00:34:33.083
Very good. Well done. everyone. Well done.

639
00:34:33.166 --> 00:34:34.333
One by one.

640
00:34:34.416 --> 00:34:36.375
-Very good.
-Wait. wait. there's a baby.

641
00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:39.708
-What's your name?
-Rose.

642
00:34:39.791 --> 00:34:42.125
Rose. my name is Mauro.
And what's your baby's name?

643
00:34:43.208 --> 00:34:44.125
Pride.

644
00:34:44.208 --> 00:34:46.416
Okay so. Rose. I'll take Pride
only for one minute. okay?

645
00:34:46.500 --> 00:34:49.125
It's too dangerous for you to climb
on the vessel with him.

646
00:34:49.208 --> 00:34:51.000
Trust me. I'll take care of Pride.

647
00:34:57.083 --> 00:34:58.458
-Okay.
-Okay?

648
00:34:59.333 --> 00:35:00.250
Okay.

649
00:35:01.833 --> 00:35:03.333
[Lukas] I'll help you. okay?

650
00:35:08.041 --> 00:35:10.208
[Lukas] The mother.
and then we'll continue. all right?

651
00:35:13.166 --> 00:35:14.875
Your turn. okay?

652
00:35:14.958 --> 00:35:17.458
I'll help you over. Come on.

653
00:35:18.833 --> 00:35:20.250
Okay. She's really worried.

654
00:35:20.333 --> 00:35:22.666
I'm gonna take your baby
for a few seconds. okay?

655
00:35:22.750 --> 00:35:26.041
[Lukas] Wait. one second.
We need to wait for the baby to be safe.

656
00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:28.875
Just wait for a second.

657
00:35:28.958 --> 00:35:31.416
You're safe. Everything's fine.

658
00:35:31.500 --> 00:35:33.291
There you go. I got you. I got you.

659
00:35:33.375 --> 00:35:35.083
-You can do it. Almost.
-We want to help.

660
00:35:35.166 --> 00:35:37.916
Everything's fine.
You're safe now. all right?

661
00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:40.000
[passengers chanting]

662
00:35:42.375 --> 00:35:46.416
[melancholic music playing]

663
00:36:06.583 --> 00:36:07.916
-Paula.
-Yeah?

664
00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:09.208
There's a boat.

665
00:36:09.916 --> 00:36:11.125
Sören from Maik.

666
00:36:12.083 --> 00:36:12.916
[Sören] <i>Yes?</i>

667
00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:15.916
Yeah. we see a boat coming.
I think they're engine fishermen.

668
00:36:17.041 --> 00:36:20.125
Okay. don't take unnecessary risks.
Come back. please.

669
00:36:20.208 --> 00:36:21.333
Okay. copy.

670
00:36:22.750 --> 00:36:24.125
-Ready?
-Yeah.

671
00:36:24.208 --> 00:36:26.125
-Okay. let's go.
-Whoa.

672
00:36:26.208 --> 00:36:27.833
[fisher shouts]

673
00:36:27.916 --> 00:36:30.416
[Maik] Engine's gone! We sank it!
Nothing to take here!

674
00:36:32.083 --> 00:36:34.083
[fishermen shouting]

675
00:36:38.625 --> 00:36:40.541
-[Sören] You all right?
-[Maik] <i>Everything's fine.</i>

676
00:36:40.625 --> 00:36:42.208
-<i>On our way</i>.
-[Sören] Okay. great.

677
00:36:43.041 --> 00:36:46.166
[Su] You have a little wound here
caused by the fuel of the boat.

678
00:36:46.250 --> 00:36:49.833
So I'm gonna clean it. disinfect it.
and put a bandage on it. okay?

679
00:36:49.916 --> 00:36:51.958
It might hurt a little bit.

680
00:36:55.291 --> 00:36:56.291
Hey.

681
00:36:58.666 --> 00:37:00.916
-Thank you.
-[Su] Where are you from?

682
00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:04.791
Nigeria. I'm from Nigeria.

683
00:37:04.875 --> 00:37:06.958
From small village.

684
00:37:07.041 --> 00:37:09.041
-Sorry.
-In the northeast.

685
00:37:09.125 --> 00:37:11.083
How old are you?

686
00:37:11.166 --> 00:37:12.541
Eighteen.

687
00:37:13.791 --> 00:37:15.166
[Mauro] And how old is he?

688
00:37:18.125 --> 00:37:20.500
Six months. And three days.

689
00:37:21.083 --> 00:37:22.083
[Su] Mm.

690
00:37:22.833 --> 00:37:26.000
And why did you… I mean.
why did you leave Nigeria?

691
00:37:29.833 --> 00:37:32.333
I was living in my village
when Boko Haram came.

692
00:37:33.083 --> 00:37:34.416
They are killing people.

693
00:37:34.500 --> 00:37:39.791
They come to the fields where we work
and rape the women and kill the men.

694
00:37:39.875 --> 00:37:43.541
So I was running from my village
to the city.

695
00:37:45.250 --> 00:37:46.833
But I had no house.

696
00:37:48.333 --> 00:37:50.041
So it was not easy there.

697
00:37:51.333 --> 00:37:54.166
What was the situation on the boat?

698
00:37:55.125 --> 00:37:56.625
[Rose] Very scary.

699
00:37:56.708 --> 00:37:59.500
We were so many. We were squeezed.

700
00:37:59.583 --> 00:38:04.875
People are vomiting.
It was my first time at sea.

701
00:38:06.500 --> 00:38:08.000
You can't swim?

702
00:38:08.791 --> 00:38:11.541
No. Many of us cannot swim.

703
00:38:11.625 --> 00:38:13.500
It is just life or death.

704
00:38:16.208 --> 00:38:18.208
-And the sea is so big.
-Yeah.

705
00:38:18.291 --> 00:38:19.833
So. so big.

706
00:38:21.791 --> 00:38:23.375
And I was scared.

707
00:38:25.541 --> 00:38:29.000
And Pride cried.
And I just wanted him to live.

708
00:38:29.083 --> 00:38:31.291
You know. it's all I could think of.

709
00:38:31.375 --> 00:38:34.250
[sighs sadly]

710
00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:39.000
[indistinct radio chatter]

711
00:38:45.250 --> 00:38:48.791
[Lukas] <i>Okay. everyone.</i>
<i>Can I have your attention for a moment?</i>

712
00:38:50.041 --> 00:38:52.708
There's a small boat approaching
on that side

713
00:38:52.791 --> 00:38:56.375
that will take you to a much bigger boat
from the Italian coast guard.

714
00:38:56.458 --> 00:38:59.833
They will take care of you.
bring you to safety. and to Italy.

715
00:38:59.916 --> 00:39:03.750
Because we only rescue.
but they will bring you to Europe. okay?

716
00:39:03.833 --> 00:39:04.833
Thank you.

717
00:39:10.625 --> 00:39:13.625
-Thank you for your help on the boat.
-You're welcome.

718
00:39:13.708 --> 00:39:16.375
-Thank you for your help.
-[chuckles]

719
00:39:16.958 --> 00:39:19.833
It was my first. uh. time. you know?

720
00:39:19.916 --> 00:39:21.708
You did a great job.

721
00:39:21.791 --> 00:39:23.666
[Lukas chuckles] We all did. we all did.

722
00:39:24.500 --> 00:39:26.583
How long have you been traveling?

723
00:39:27.500 --> 00:39:29.208
I traveled for three years.

724
00:39:29.291 --> 00:39:32.333
And… why did you leave?

725
00:39:33.583 --> 00:39:35.333
My father is very ill.

726
00:39:35.416 --> 00:39:40.583
He lost his job.
and we have no money for food.

727
00:39:40.666 --> 00:39:42.166
No money for medicine.

728
00:39:43.458 --> 00:39:46.666
You know. I wanted to be educated.

729
00:39:47.250 --> 00:39:49.500
I wanted to be a very educated man.

730
00:39:49.583 --> 00:39:50.791
That's my plan.

731
00:39:51.291 --> 00:39:53.916
I am praying to God that it will happen.

732
00:39:54.791 --> 00:39:56.333
And you traveled all by yourself?

733
00:39:56.416 --> 00:39:59.041
No. I traveled with a friend.

734
00:40:00.041 --> 00:40:02.250
And… is he here now?

735
00:40:03.958 --> 00:40:05.166
He's dead.

736
00:40:05.958 --> 00:40:08.291
We worked in a gold mine in Burkina Faso.

737
00:40:08.958 --> 00:40:11.458
It was very hot. Fifty degrees.

738
00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:13.541
Many people died.

739
00:40:18.208 --> 00:40:21.750
But you have a good job here on board.

740
00:40:22.416 --> 00:40:26.708
-[Lukas chuckles]
-You do good. You travel. You get paid.

741
00:40:26.791 --> 00:40:28.916
No. no. we're not getting paid.

742
00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:31.041
-You don't get paid?
-No.

743
00:40:31.125 --> 00:40:35.041
Oh. Then it's a… it's a shitty job.

744
00:40:35.125 --> 00:40:36.541
[laughs]

745
00:40:36.625 --> 00:40:38.666
Yeah. I guess it's a shitty job. then.

746
00:40:38.750 --> 00:40:40.666
-Only joking.
-[chuckles]

747
00:40:40.750 --> 00:40:43.166
You saved our lives.

748
00:40:44.875 --> 00:40:46.208
It's a good job.

749
00:40:52.875 --> 00:40:54.791
[Lukas] One big step.

750
00:40:54.875 --> 00:40:56.625
-[man] Yes. that's it.
-Thank you.

751
00:40:56.708 --> 00:40:58.833
-[Lukas] Goodbye. man.
-Thank you.

752
00:40:58.916 --> 00:41:00.583
[hopeful music playing]

753
00:41:00.666 --> 00:41:03.500
-Can you please hold Pride for me?
-Of course.

754
00:41:06.666 --> 00:41:09.041
-I'll help you over. okay?
-[Rose] Thank you.

755
00:41:09.958 --> 00:41:11.125
Well done.

756
00:41:11.791 --> 00:41:15.166
Be careful with his head. Careful.

757
00:41:22.583 --> 00:41:24.333
-[Lukas] Take care.
-Goodbye.

758
00:41:26.916 --> 00:41:29.125
-Goodbye.
-Goodbye. Lukas.

759
00:41:29.666 --> 00:41:31.333
-Lukas.
-[Lukas] Yes?

760
00:41:32.958 --> 00:41:34.416
Please have this.

761
00:41:35.083 --> 00:41:37.458
Thank you. Thank you so much.

762
00:41:37.541 --> 00:41:38.833
Thank you. Lukas.

763
00:41:38.916 --> 00:41:40.375
Now you are my friend.

764
00:41:42.041 --> 00:41:44.333
-Take care.
-Bye. Lukas.

765
00:42:43.041 --> 00:42:44.541
[sniffles]

766
00:42:51.166 --> 00:42:52.916
[cheering]

767
00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:54.583
[all exclaim]

768
00:42:55.291 --> 00:42:56.500
[screams]

769
00:42:59.291 --> 00:43:01.291
[group exclaims]

770
00:43:05.250 --> 00:43:06.791
[cheering]

771
00:43:23.875 --> 00:43:26.125
-Whoo!
-This is great.

772
00:43:26.208 --> 00:43:27.666
[music fades]

773
00:43:33.500 --> 00:43:35.500
[guitar strumming]

774
00:43:49.458 --> 00:43:50.875
Today on the boat…

775
00:43:54.625 --> 00:43:59.250
that moment I held Rose's baby… Pride.

776
00:43:59.750 --> 00:44:02.916
[chuckles] It's like
the weight of the world was on me.

777
00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:04.166
You know?

778
00:44:05.250 --> 00:44:09.041
It's the first time in my life
I held a baby. What a feeling.

779
00:44:11.375 --> 00:44:13.625
I was constantly telling myself.

780
00:44:14.875 --> 00:44:16.666
"Do not drop it. Mauro."

781
00:44:18.041 --> 00:44:20.166
"Protect Pride with your life."

782
00:44:21.333 --> 00:44:24.458
"You'll never do anything
more important than this."

783
00:44:35.958 --> 00:44:38.125
FIRST MISSION 2016
JULY 29. DAY 06

784
00:44:38.208 --> 00:44:40.041
30 NAUTICAL MILES OFF LIBYA

785
00:44:40.541 --> 00:44:44.583
If you want to say something like.
"My name's Paula" or "I'm Lukas or Maik."

786
00:44:44.666 --> 00:44:46.833
then you say. "<i>Ana Paula</i>."

787
00:44:46.916 --> 00:44:48.125
-<i>Ana</i>…
-<i>Ana Lukas.</i>

788
00:44:48.208 --> 00:44:49.041
<i>Ana Mauro.</i>

789
00:44:49.125 --> 00:44:50.375
-<i>Ana Maik.</i>
<i>-"Ana Maik." </i>yeah.

790
00:44:50.458 --> 00:44:52.250
[grunts] Welcome.

791
00:44:52.375 --> 00:44:54.541
[passengers clamoring]

792
00:44:55.750 --> 00:44:56.750
Welcome.

793
00:44:56.833 --> 00:44:57.875
I'm Marietta.

794
00:44:57.958 --> 00:44:59.083
-Marietta?
-Yes.

795
00:44:59.166 --> 00:45:00.583
-That's a beautiful name.
-Thank you.

796
00:45:00.666 --> 00:45:02.541
Nice to meet you. Hey. I'm Sören.

797
00:45:02.625 --> 00:45:05.208
Boat at 135 degrees!

798
00:45:05.291 --> 00:45:08.916
[Sören] We see the boat.
Straight ahead. two o'clock.

799
00:45:09.583 --> 00:45:11.583
[passengers chanting]

800
00:45:14.916 --> 00:45:17.500
[woman] I'm born in Eritrea.

801
00:45:17.583 --> 00:45:23.625
But I had to leave
after… my family was killed by government.

802
00:45:23.708 --> 00:45:27.041
<i>But in Sudan. they say</i>
<i>I have to marry a very old man.</i>

803
00:45:27.125 --> 00:45:29.791
<i>Very older than me.</i>

804
00:45:29.875 --> 00:45:34.208
So… I decide to flee again.

805
00:45:34.916 --> 00:45:36.625
[cheering]

806
00:45:56.250 --> 00:45:58.083
Look! Dolphins!

807
00:45:58.166 --> 00:46:00.000
-[Mauro] No way!
-[Lukas] Yes!

808
00:46:00.916 --> 00:46:02.250
-No!
-Yeah!

809
00:46:02.333 --> 00:46:04.083
-[all laugh]
-[Mauro] God damn!

810
00:46:04.166 --> 00:46:05.708
[man on radio] <i>Good morning. Iuventa.</i>

811
00:46:05.791 --> 00:46:07.791
<i>We have the first sighting of the day.</i>

812
00:46:07.875 --> 00:46:09.833
<i>It is a blue wooden boat.</i>

813
00:46:09.916 --> 00:46:14.583
<i>You can go on the longitude.</i>
<i>I'm waiting for… waiting for my orders.</i>

814
00:46:14.666 --> 00:46:16.250
We'll proceed with the rescue.

815
00:46:16.333 --> 00:46:17.833
-[man] <i>Perfect. Thank you.</i>
-Thank you.

816
00:46:21.208 --> 00:46:22.916
[indistinct chatter]

817
00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:24.416
-One. two. three.
-I'm done.

818
00:46:24.500 --> 00:46:26.250
[gasps] Mwah. I love you.

819
00:46:26.333 --> 00:46:28.333
-[group laughing]
-That one looks like Mauro!

820
00:46:32.125 --> 00:46:34.833
You all right? Stay safe.

821
00:46:34.916 --> 00:46:37.291
-Bye. all the best.
-Bye. all the best. all right? Okay?

822
00:46:38.041 --> 00:46:40.041
[excited chatter]

823
00:46:42.875 --> 00:46:44.875
[music fades]

824
00:47:11.208 --> 00:47:15.583
[shouting]

825
00:47:19.750 --> 00:47:21.916
Pass the woman over to us. okay?

826
00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:24.333
[loud clamoring]

827
00:47:24.916 --> 00:47:27.833
-Okay. carefully. carefully.
-[man] No. Fatima!

828
00:47:27.916 --> 00:47:29.083
Careful. please.

829
00:47:29.166 --> 00:47:30.250
[man] Fatima!

830
00:47:30.333 --> 00:47:31.875
[screaming]

831
00:47:34.333 --> 00:47:36.125
Okay. go back. go back!

832
00:47:41.458 --> 00:47:43.458
No. no. go back. Go back. please.

833
00:47:43.541 --> 00:47:46.250
Go back. Please stay calm.
Everybody. stay calm.

834
00:47:46.333 --> 00:47:49.500
You've got your life vests.
Hold on to them. okay?

835
00:47:49.583 --> 00:47:51.625
Hold on to them and go back to the boat.

836
00:47:51.708 --> 00:47:54.833
Please. stay calm. okay?
The life vests help you.

837
00:47:54.916 --> 00:47:57.125
You're safe. but you have to go back.

838
00:47:59.916 --> 00:48:01.875
[clamoring]

839
00:48:03.416 --> 00:48:04.750
Okay.

840
00:48:08.375 --> 00:48:09.666
Contact!

841
00:48:14.583 --> 00:48:15.625
What's her name?

842
00:48:15.708 --> 00:48:17.458
Fatima. Fatima!

843
00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:19.125
Fatima.

844
00:48:19.708 --> 00:48:22.625
-We cannot take you. Sorry--
-No. I have to stay with her!

845
00:48:22.708 --> 00:48:25.333
We're gonna take her to a bigger ship
and then to a doctor. okay?

846
00:48:25.416 --> 00:48:28.083
-I'm her brother!
-We're gonna come back. I promise.

847
00:48:28.166 --> 00:48:29.666
No!

848
00:48:29.750 --> 00:48:31.875
-[shouting]
-No!

849
00:48:31.958 --> 00:48:33.750
[Mauro] Iuventa. RHIB.

850
00:48:33.833 --> 00:48:35.208
We have two people on board.

851
00:48:35.291 --> 00:48:37.791
one unconscious.
and we've started resuscitation.

852
00:48:37.875 --> 00:48:40.791
Roger that. We'll prepare everything.
I'll give Su a heads-up.

853
00:48:40.875 --> 00:48:42.125
Hang in there.

854
00:48:44.833 --> 00:48:50.083
[Lukas] 22. 23. 24.
25. 26. 27. 28. 29. 30.

855
00:48:51.833 --> 00:48:53.500
-Go.
-One. two. three…

856
00:48:55.208 --> 00:48:57.208
[Lukas panting]

857
00:48:57.916 --> 00:49:00.708
…26. 27. 28. 29. 30.

858
00:49:00.791 --> 00:49:02.250
[grunts]

859
00:49:02.333 --> 00:49:04.333
-She's not breathing. It's not working!
-Wait!

860
00:49:04.416 --> 00:49:05.833
It's not working!

861
00:49:13.750 --> 00:49:15.583
Go. go. go. go. go!

862
00:49:15.666 --> 00:49:17.666
[tense music playing]

863
00:49:17.750 --> 00:49:20.666
[Su] One. two. three. four. five…

864
00:49:21.666 --> 00:49:23.041
Ten.

865
00:49:23.625 --> 00:49:24.958
Fifteen.

866
00:49:25.791 --> 00:49:26.791
Twenty…

867
00:49:27.500 --> 00:49:30.708
25. 26. 27. 8. 9. 10. Go!

868
00:49:39.041 --> 00:49:40.333
Do one more.

869
00:49:48.583 --> 00:49:50.583
[sighs]

870
00:49:50.666 --> 00:49:52.000
[Lukas panting]

871
00:49:52.083 --> 00:49:53.041
Lukas.

872
00:49:53.125 --> 00:49:55.250
-[softly] Five.
-It's over.

873
00:49:55.333 --> 00:49:57.666
-Ten.
-Hey. Lukas.

874
00:49:57.750 --> 00:49:58.833
Fifteen.

875
00:49:58.916 --> 00:50:00.166
-Hey. Lukas.
-Twenty.

876
00:50:00.250 --> 00:50:02.583
-[Su] Lukas. Lukas?
-Twenty-five.

877
00:50:02.666 --> 00:50:04.333
Lukas? Lukas. please. Lukas.

878
00:50:04.416 --> 00:50:05.833
-Thirty.
-[Su] Hey. hey…

879
00:50:05.916 --> 00:50:08.958
-Lukas. it's not helping.
-[Su] Lukas! Lukas.

880
00:50:09.041 --> 00:50:10.750
It's over. Okay?

881
00:50:10.833 --> 00:50:12.041
She's dead.

882
00:50:12.125 --> 00:50:14.000
[panting]

883
00:50:14.083 --> 00:50:15.583
She's dead.

884
00:50:18.750 --> 00:50:20.750
[music fades]

885
00:50:36.833 --> 00:50:39.791
You couldn't have saved her. Lukas.

886
00:50:42.708 --> 00:50:48.416
It doesn't make it less painful.
I know. but you couldn't have saved her.

887
00:50:50.208 --> 00:50:54.583
She was already gone
when you brought her on the boat.

888
00:50:56.708 --> 00:50:58.208
You know that. right?

889
00:51:01.833 --> 00:51:02.833
Hey.

890
00:51:05.916 --> 00:51:08.875
It's really important that you know that.

891
00:51:21.333 --> 00:51:24.041
END OF THE FIRST MISSION
BERLIN. 16 AUGUST 2016

892
00:51:24.125 --> 00:51:25.958
CREW CHANGE ON THE IUVENTA

893
00:51:26.041 --> 00:51:28.791
-[Nina] Hi.
-[Kitty] You're back! [chuckles]

894
00:51:28.875 --> 00:51:30.625
-Oh my gosh!
-[Mauro] Good to see you!

895
00:51:30.708 --> 00:51:32.041
[Kitty] It's so good to see you!

896
00:51:55.166 --> 00:51:56.625
[Lukas] <i>It feels so absurd</i>

897
00:51:56.708 --> 00:51:59.333
<i>that the weather's</i>
<i>always so beautiful down there.</i>

898
00:52:01.541 --> 00:52:04.458
<i>The sun shines so bright.</i>
<i>The sea's totally calm.</i>

899
00:52:06.541 --> 00:52:08.708
At night it's completely quiet.

900
00:52:11.583 --> 00:52:14.416
And you just sit there. knowing

901
00:52:14.958 --> 00:52:17.916
the rubber dinghies are going out
to sea at that moment.

902
00:52:20.666 --> 00:52:22.875
The people we meet have often gone
through an odyssey

903
00:52:22.958 --> 00:52:24.875
that's lasted for years.

904
00:52:27.625 --> 00:52:29.708
They come to us on the Iuventa.

905
00:52:31.166 --> 00:52:32.708
And they kiss the deck.

906
00:52:33.750 --> 00:52:35.958
They lift their arms to the sky.

907
00:52:37.166 --> 00:52:39.333
They're just so delighted.

908
00:52:41.458 --> 00:52:44.333
-They're thrilled they're finally safe.
-Mm.

909
00:52:47.416 --> 00:52:50.375
But we know it's far from over
for them at that point.

910
00:52:54.583 --> 00:52:56.958
You can't tell them. though.
It's not the time to.

911
00:53:30.958 --> 00:53:33.750
[distant shouting]

912
00:54:03.333 --> 00:54:05.333
[clamoring grows louder]

913
00:54:08.166 --> 00:54:10.583
[water rushing]

914
00:54:15.083 --> 00:54:16.750
[Lukas] <i>We are from Europe.</i>

915
00:54:16.833 --> 00:54:20.375
<i>We're here to help you. You're safe now!</i>

916
00:54:24.083 --> 00:54:25.750
<i>Is everyone all right?</i>

917
00:54:26.541 --> 00:54:28.500
-<i>No. wait! No fighting!</i>
-[Lamin] <i>Wait!</i>

918
00:54:28.583 --> 00:54:31.708
[Lukas] <i>We've got enough for everyone.</i>
<i>No fighting. please!</i>

919
00:54:31.791 --> 00:54:33.750
<i>Go back. go back! What's her name?</i>

920
00:54:33.833 --> 00:54:35.625
[brother] <i>No. Fatima!</i>

921
00:54:35.708 --> 00:54:37.750
<i>-Fatima!</i>
-[woman] <i>Please. please.</i>

922
00:54:37.833 --> 00:54:39.166
-[Lukas] <i>Go!</i>
-[man] <i>Lukas!</i>

923
00:54:39.250 --> 00:54:40.916
[Lukas] <i>Go! Go!</i>

924
00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:44.541
-[brother] <i>Where are you taking her?</i>
-[Lukas] <i>We cannot. we cannot take you!</i>

925
00:54:44.625 --> 00:54:47.208
-[brother] <i>I'm her brother!</i>
-[Lukas] <i>We're gonna come back. promise!</i>

926
00:54:47.291 --> 00:54:49.291
-[Su] <i>She's dead.</i>
-[brother] <i>No!</i>

927
00:54:49.375 --> 00:54:50.875
[silence falls]

928
00:55:02.833 --> 00:55:04.041
[gasps]

929
00:55:21.750 --> 00:55:23.750
[breathing shakily]

930
00:55:31.791 --> 00:55:32.791
[sighs]

931
00:55:42.541 --> 00:55:44.541
[gentle music playing]

932
00:55:49.458 --> 00:55:55.000
I'm here with Lukas. Nina.
Domi. and Mauro from Jugend Rettet.

933
00:55:55.083 --> 00:55:58.958
I really want us to go over how people
can get involved with the cause.

934
00:55:59.041 --> 00:56:01.541
But before we do. I'd like us to find out

935
00:56:01.625 --> 00:56:04.750
what our listeners' thoughts are
on what you're doing.

936
00:56:04.833 --> 00:56:07.750
Isn't it normal to save these poor folks?

937
00:56:07.833 --> 00:56:10.375
Should we be ashamed of questioning that?

938
00:56:10.458 --> 00:56:14.250
Joining us on the phone.
I have Christian from Schöneberg.

939
00:56:14.333 --> 00:56:15.583
[Christian] <i>Yeah. hi! Um…</i>

940
00:56:15.666 --> 00:56:19.041
<i>Let me start by saying</i>
<i>that I really appreciate you all helping.</i>

941
00:56:19.125 --> 00:56:20.416
<i>The thing that I'm not getting</i>

942
00:56:20.500 --> 00:56:23.791
<i>is why aren't you taking</i>
<i>these people back to Africa?</i>

943
00:56:23.875 --> 00:56:26.625
<i>-Why do they all end up in Europe?</i>
-You take it.

944
00:56:27.208 --> 00:56:29.458
Well. according to
the Geneva Refugee Convention.

945
00:56:29.541 --> 00:56:32.416
we're not allowed to return anyone
to an unsafe country.

946
00:56:32.500 --> 00:56:34.500
Libya is an unsafe country.
and we would've gone

947
00:56:34.583 --> 00:56:36.208
against the law had we done so.

948
00:56:36.291 --> 00:56:39.166
Honestly. it's not just
that it's against the law.

949
00:56:39.250 --> 00:56:40.833
They would get thrown into prison.

950
00:56:40.916 --> 00:56:43.291
tortured. and would possibly die
if we took them back.

951
00:56:43.375 --> 00:56:46.458
[Christian] <i>All right. but why not</i>
<i>take them to some other African country</i>

952
00:56:46.541 --> 00:56:47.666
<i>where they'd be safe?</i>

953
00:56:47.750 --> 00:56:49.916
<i>I just don't understand</i>
<i>why they all have to come here.</i>

954
00:56:50.000 --> 00:56:52.291
'Cause Germany offers
the right to asylum. Christian.

955
00:56:52.375 --> 00:56:55.166
[Christian] <i>Yeah. but that</i>
<i>doesn't make it okay to take everyone in.</i>

956
00:56:55.250 --> 00:56:58.333
<i>Our problems won't get any better</i>
<i>if we take in more migrants.</i>

957
00:56:58.416 --> 00:57:00.250
-Tell me. Christian?
<i>-Yes?</i>

958
00:57:00.333 --> 00:57:01.541
What scares you exactly?

959
00:57:01.625 --> 00:57:03.500
<i>Not feeling comfortable in my country.</i>

960
00:57:03.583 --> 00:57:05.583
<i>letting criminals in.</i>
<i>and my children not being safe.</i>

961
00:57:05.666 --> 00:57:08.625
<i>I'm afraid we won't be able to handle</i>
<i>the added pressure as a country.</i>

962
00:57:08.708 --> 00:57:11.541
<i>I mean. I think it's great</i>
<i>and all that you're helping people</i>

963
00:57:11.625 --> 00:57:15.416
<i>in the Mediterranean. but you're certainly</i>
<i>not helping people in Germany.</i>

964
00:57:15.500 --> 00:57:17.083
<i>That's what I think. Nice talking to you.</i>

965
00:57:17.166 --> 00:57:18.916
-Christian--
-<i>Bye.</i>

966
00:57:19.000 --> 00:57:21.916
-[call disconnects]
-[Domi sighs]

967
00:57:26.750 --> 00:57:29.791
THIRD MISSION 2016. 29 SEPTEMBER. DAY 09
INTERNATIONAL WATERS OFF LIBYA

968
00:57:29.875 --> 00:57:33.125
[Maik] Okay. so we should all be
at 65 degrees now.

969
00:57:33.208 --> 00:57:34.541
-Yeah?
-[Paula] Yes.

970
00:57:34.625 --> 00:57:38.125
[Maik] 65 degrees is the bearing
you would give to the bridge.

971
00:57:38.208 --> 00:57:39.041
-Okay?
-Yeah.

972
00:57:39.125 --> 00:57:41.125
[strumming gentle tune]

973
00:57:52.083 --> 00:57:53.500
[gasps softly]

974
00:57:56.000 --> 00:57:58.000
Sören. can you please come to the bridge?

975
00:57:58.958 --> 00:58:01.791
Hang on. Wait.
I'll call you back. all right?

976
00:58:01.875 --> 00:58:03.583
[tense music playing]

977
00:58:03.666 --> 00:58:04.500
Yeah?

978
00:58:04.583 --> 00:58:08.125
Yeah. a speedboat is approaching us.
Way too fast from the south.

979
00:58:08.208 --> 00:58:09.916
No idea who it is. They're not answering.

980
00:58:10.000 --> 00:58:12.750
-Uh. are they militia?
-[Sören] <i>Maybe. We don't know.</i>

981
00:58:12.833 --> 00:58:14.333
We've begun the lockdown procedure.

982
00:58:14.416 --> 00:58:16.416
Su is escorting everyone
to the engine room.

983
00:58:16.500 --> 00:58:17.666
<i>I'm going on deck now.</i>

984
00:58:17.750 --> 00:58:20.458
De-escalation.
You mind staying on the line?

985
00:58:20.541 --> 00:58:21.833
Of course. yeah.

986
00:58:25.791 --> 00:58:29.083
[Su] We do it the way we trained.
We stay in the engine room and wait.

987
00:58:29.166 --> 00:58:30.666
We won't risk anything.

988
00:58:31.750 --> 00:58:33.000
Come on. go.

989
00:58:35.375 --> 00:58:36.583
[Sören] Engine room.

990
00:58:38.458 --> 00:58:40.458
[ominous music rises]

991
00:58:43.708 --> 00:58:45.916
Shit. Viola. They look armed.

992
00:58:46.791 --> 00:58:49.166
All stations. all stations. all stations.

993
00:58:49.250 --> 00:58:51.625
This is Iuventa. Iuventa. Iuventa.

994
00:58:51.708 --> 00:58:54.208
I am 15 miles northwest from Tripoli.

995
00:58:54.291 --> 00:58:56.916
I have a pirate attack.
I repeat. I have a pirate attack.

996
00:58:57.000 --> 00:58:58.208
I need urgent help.

997
00:58:58.291 --> 00:59:00.125
-Slow down!
-[man shouting]

998
00:59:00.208 --> 00:59:02.458
-Hey. slow down!
-[shouting]

999
00:59:02.541 --> 00:59:04.166
-[gunfire]
-[grunts]

1000
00:59:04.250 --> 00:59:07.333
Hey. no shooting! No! No shooting.

1001
00:59:07.416 --> 00:59:08.833
Please. no shooting.

1002
00:59:08.916 --> 00:59:10.416
We do search and rescue.

1003
00:59:10.500 --> 00:59:13.791
We do search and rescue.
We have… We don't have a problem.

1004
00:59:13.875 --> 00:59:16.041
-[gasps]
-[gunfire on radio]

1005
00:59:16.125 --> 00:59:20.083
[Sören] <i>Please. We do search</i>
<i>and rescue. We're… We're friendly.</i>

1006
00:59:20.166 --> 00:59:22.916
We have no problem here.
Everything is fine here.

1007
00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:24.791
-What do you want?
-Yes.

1008
00:59:24.875 --> 00:59:26.125
[speaking Arabic]

1009
00:59:26.208 --> 00:59:27.583
-Everything is fine.
-Where is crew?

1010
00:59:27.666 --> 00:59:30.125
-[man speaking Arabic]
-Everything is fine.

1011
00:59:30.208 --> 00:59:31.916
Hey! Come on. stop. Come on. stop!

1012
00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:33.666
-[speaking Arabic]
-What do you want?

1013
00:59:33.750 --> 00:59:36.125
[Su] Come on. come down.
We're staying here. okay?

1014
00:59:36.208 --> 00:59:37.541
Watch your head. Be careful.

1015
00:59:37.625 --> 00:59:39.125
The engine is really hot.

1016
00:59:39.208 --> 00:59:40.291
[hatch opens]

1017
00:59:40.375 --> 00:59:41.875
Where are the others?

1018
00:59:41.958 --> 00:59:44.250
[nearby shouting]

1019
00:59:45.250 --> 00:59:47.583
-Hey. why are you doing this?
-[speaking Arabic]

1020
00:59:47.666 --> 00:59:49.291
There's no one here. okay?

1021
00:59:51.791 --> 00:59:54.291
-[Su] It's all right. okay?
-[gasps]

1022
00:59:54.375 --> 00:59:55.625
[shouting above]

1023
00:59:58.375 --> 01:00:02.750
[Sören] Please don't. Stop. Hey! Hey!

1024
01:00:02.833 --> 01:00:05.083
Please. please be calm.
Please be calm.

1025
01:00:05.166 --> 01:00:07.125
[shouting in Arabic]

1026
01:00:07.958 --> 01:00:09.083
[man 1] Crew.

1027
01:00:09.166 --> 01:00:10.833
Crew. Where's crew?

1028
01:00:10.916 --> 01:00:13.541
[shouting continues above]

1029
01:00:13.625 --> 01:00:15.666
-[man 2 speaking Arabic]
-Okay. My name is Su.

1030
01:00:15.750 --> 01:00:17.250
My name is Su.

1031
01:00:17.333 --> 01:00:20.083
I'm the doctor on this vessel.
Please! I'm the doctor. leave them!

1032
01:00:20.166 --> 01:00:21.875
[man 2 shouting]

1033
01:00:21.958 --> 01:00:24.708
Iuventa. Iuventa. Iuventa.
Armed groups are boarding our ship.

1034
01:00:25.666 --> 01:00:26.500
[speaks Arabic]

1035
01:00:26.583 --> 01:00:30.041
We are a search and rescue organization.
We're here to save people at sea.

1036
01:00:30.125 --> 01:00:32.333
-Viola?
-[Sören] <i>We're peaceful. We help people.</i>

1037
01:00:32.416 --> 01:00:34.875
-Sören?
-[man shouting in Arabic]

1038
01:00:34.958 --> 01:00:38.333
-Hey! We are a rescue mission.
-Walk! Walk!

1039
01:00:38.416 --> 01:00:39.541
-[Viola] Hey!
-Move.

1040
01:00:39.625 --> 01:00:41.708
-Hey! Hey. hey. hey. hey. hey. hey.
-Stand aside!

1041
01:00:41.791 --> 01:00:43.708
Passports. Give me passports.

1042
01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:50.416
This is national water.

1043
01:00:50.500 --> 01:00:53.541
This is international waters.
You can't just board my ship like this.

1044
01:00:53.625 --> 01:00:55.250
-We did nothing wrong.
-No!

1045
01:00:57.791 --> 01:01:01.708
-This is Libyan country. No rescue here.
-This is international waters!

1046
01:01:11.375 --> 01:01:14.541
As long as I see Libyan mountains.
this is my water.

1047
01:01:15.375 --> 01:01:18.708
Next time we see you. we arrest you.
And we'll bring you to jail.

1048
01:01:19.208 --> 01:01:22.000
Next time we see you in our water.
we sink this ship.

1049
01:01:22.083 --> 01:01:23.375
You understand?

1050
01:01:24.166 --> 01:01:28.208
[exhales shakily] Understood.

1051
01:01:30.916 --> 01:01:32.250
[music ends]

1052
01:01:47.416 --> 01:01:49.416
[boat engine retreating]

1053
01:01:59.666 --> 01:02:01.291
[Sören] <i>So. I talked to the crew.</i>

1054
01:02:01.375 --> 01:02:04.583
<i>We took a vote.</i>
<i>and we would all like to continue.</i>

1055
01:02:06.041 --> 01:02:08.666
I hear you. but this is
not your decision alone.

1056
01:02:08.750 --> 01:02:10.541
We can't risk a situation
like this happening.

1057
01:02:10.625 --> 01:02:12.250
<i>I mean. they were armed.</i>

1058
01:02:12.333 --> 01:02:14.458
Lukas. we're aware of that. We were here.

1059
01:02:14.541 --> 01:02:17.875
We just think you should take a break
for a couple of weeks. that's all.

1060
01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:20.750
And we'll do a new danger assessment
and adjust.

1061
01:02:20.833 --> 01:02:23.166
What about those people in Libya
getting on boats tonight?

1062
01:02:23.250 --> 01:02:25.583
-I bet <i>they </i>want a break.
<i>-Drop the attitude. Viola.</i>

1063
01:02:25.666 --> 01:02:26.625
We were down there too.

1064
01:02:26.708 --> 01:02:28.833
You're not the only one
who knows how bad it is.

1065
01:02:28.916 --> 01:02:31.541
If we stay on mission.
it'll send the right message.

1066
01:02:31.625 --> 01:02:34.375
That they can't intimidate us.
Or else. they've won.

1067
01:02:34.458 --> 01:02:35.875
<i>You understand me?</i>

1068
01:02:38.583 --> 01:02:39.958
It's your choice.

1069
01:02:46.916 --> 01:02:48.333
Okay. We'll go back to Malta.

1070
01:02:48.416 --> 01:02:50.791
<i>take a break.</i>
<i>and prepare for the next mission.</i>

1071
01:02:52.583 --> 01:02:54.666
-[sighs]
-Okay.

1072
01:02:55.750 --> 01:02:57.208
We'll have to go with that.

1073
01:02:57.291 --> 01:02:58.291
Yup.

1074
01:02:58.375 --> 01:03:00.541
[Viola] <i>So that's the signal</i>
<i>you want to send?</i>

1075
01:03:00.625 --> 01:03:02.291
At least you're not in danger.

1076
01:03:04.750 --> 01:03:05.791
[sighs]

1077
01:03:12.583 --> 01:03:14.291
[Kitty] That's Chimamanda Ngozi's

1078
01:03:14.375 --> 01:03:16.666
whole point
in "The Danger of a Single Story."

1079
01:03:16.750 --> 01:03:20.458
If you pigeonhole certain people
into a category. say poor. uneducated.

1080
01:03:20.541 --> 01:03:24.375
or powerless. and you reinforce it…
you know. by saying it over and over.

1081
01:03:24.458 --> 01:03:26.166
you start seeing it as fact.

1082
01:03:26.250 --> 01:03:31.166
The thing is… storytelling has the power
to influence our views on people.

1083
01:03:31.875 --> 01:03:33.958
I've got another example. 'kay?

1084
01:03:34.041 --> 01:03:35.583
Take the history of America.

1085
01:03:35.666 --> 01:03:37.833
Instead of focusing
on Christopher Columbus.

1086
01:03:37.916 --> 01:03:41.125
we talk about Native Americans.
the story's totally different.

1087
01:03:43.458 --> 01:03:44.458
You there?

1088
01:03:46.208 --> 01:03:48.208
[cell phone vibrating]

1089
01:03:54.500 --> 01:03:56.083
[Lamin on phone] <i>Lukas!</i>

1090
01:03:56.166 --> 01:03:57.833
-<i>My friend!</i>
-[Lukas] Lamin!

1091
01:03:58.958 --> 01:04:00.333
How… How are you?

1092
01:04:00.416 --> 01:04:03.625
Uh. sorry. Uh… I…
I've gotta take this. Wait.

1093
01:04:05.625 --> 01:04:06.625
Lamin!

1094
01:04:08.583 --> 01:04:11.583
Oh. the… the connection is really bad.
Should we switch to audio?

1095
01:04:11.666 --> 01:04:14.000
-[Lamin] <i>Yes. yes. </i>[laughs]
-Yeah.

1096
01:04:15.041 --> 01:04:17.291
How… How did you find me?

1097
01:04:17.375 --> 01:04:19.125
<i>You are on Facebook.</i>

1098
01:04:19.208 --> 01:04:21.291
Oh. right. [chuckles]

1099
01:04:21.375 --> 01:04:25.125
But. uh… how are you? Where are you now?

1100
01:04:25.208 --> 01:04:27.958
[in German] <i>I'm in Konstanz.</i>

1101
01:04:29.166 --> 01:04:30.166
[in English] What?

1102
01:04:30.250 --> 01:04:32.541
[in German] I'm in Konstanz.

1103
01:04:33.125 --> 01:04:36.083
-[in English] No way. you're not.
<i>-Yes!</i>

1104
01:04:36.166 --> 01:04:37.583
[laughs]

1105
01:04:37.666 --> 01:04:39.583
How did you get all the way there?

1106
01:04:39.666 --> 01:04:42.750
In Italy. they put me in place for minors.

1107
01:04:42.833 --> 01:04:45.125
<i>In Salerno. in small village.</i>

1108
01:04:45.208 --> 01:04:49.125
So. I asked if there is a possibility
for me to go to school.

1109
01:04:49.208 --> 01:04:51.791
You know. that was in my mind.
To be educated.

1110
01:04:52.500 --> 01:04:56.500
<i>But they told me. it's a small village.</i>
<i>they don't have a school.</i>

1111
01:04:56.583 --> 01:05:01.000
So. I got information in Germany
that you can go to school.

1112
01:05:01.083 --> 01:05:03.416
So. my plan is. "only Germany."

1113
01:05:03.500 --> 01:05:06.666
<i>I don't go anywhere. only Germany.</i>
<i>I'm going.</i>

1114
01:05:06.750 --> 01:05:09.625
-So you just went to Germany?
<i>-Yes!</i>

1115
01:05:09.750 --> 01:05:11.625
Really? But how?

1116
01:05:11.708 --> 01:05:13.000
<i>I go on train.</i>

1117
01:05:13.083 --> 01:05:15.541
And sometimes. they said
I have to leave train

1118
01:05:15.625 --> 01:05:16.833
because I have no ticket.

1119
01:05:17.458 --> 01:05:19.958
<i>And one moment. I decided to walk.</i>

1120
01:05:20.041 --> 01:05:21.833
You walked to Germany?

1121
01:05:21.916 --> 01:05:23.375
<i>Yeah! Yeah!</i>

1122
01:05:23.458 --> 01:05:27.791
<i>I walked and walked.</i>
<i>And one moment. I saw. you know.</i>

1123
01:05:27.875 --> 01:05:30.708
<i>I saw cars with the D. the D sticker.</i>

1124
01:05:30.791 --> 01:05:34.541
<i>Police came. I asked. "Am I in Germany?"</i>

1125
01:05:34.625 --> 01:05:38.791
And they were really friendly
and said. "Yes. you are in Germany."

1126
01:05:38.875 --> 01:05:39.708
<i>Incredible.</i>

1127
01:05:40.583 --> 01:05:41.750
That's so incredible.

1128
01:05:41.833 --> 01:05:46.583
<i>I called my mother. and she cried</i>
<i>because she thought I am dead.</i>

1129
01:05:47.708 --> 01:05:50.125
<i>But now. they are really happy.</i>

1130
01:05:50.208 --> 01:05:51.958
Really happy.

1131
01:05:53.375 --> 01:05:54.833
And you. my friend?

1132
01:05:54.916 --> 01:05:58.541
<i>How are you?</i>
<i>You still have this shitty job?</i>

1133
01:05:59.583 --> 01:06:02.875
[laughs] Uh. yeah.
I still have the shitty job.

1134
01:06:02.958 --> 01:06:04.916
Um. but it's okay. [chuckles]

1135
01:06:05.000 --> 01:06:08.000
I am just joking. my friend. You know?

1136
01:06:08.083 --> 01:06:10.041
No. I know. [chuckles]

1137
01:06:10.125 --> 01:06:12.083
I know. I know.

1138
01:06:12.166 --> 01:06:15.000
<i>Hey. you still have the bracelet?</i>

1139
01:06:15.083 --> 01:06:16.208
Yeah. Yes. yeah.

1140
01:06:16.291 --> 01:06:18.958
I have it with me all the time.
I wear it every day.

1141
01:06:19.916 --> 01:06:22.166
It is so good to hear you.

1142
01:06:22.250 --> 01:06:25.416
Ah. Lamin. it… it's so good
to hear your voice.

1143
01:06:25.500 --> 01:06:29.583
Really. I mean it.
It's so good to hear you.

1144
01:06:37.583 --> 01:06:39.750
-[Lukas] Hey.
-Hey.

1145
01:06:41.958 --> 01:06:43.375
Where's Kitty?

1146
01:06:43.458 --> 01:06:45.250
She's taking some time.

1147
01:06:46.541 --> 01:06:47.875
[sighs]

1148
01:06:50.250 --> 01:06:51.666
It's hard for you guys?

1149
01:06:52.875 --> 01:06:53.875
[Lukas] Mm-hmm.

1150
01:06:56.000 --> 01:06:59.833
I guess we're just
in two different worlds these days.

1151
01:07:06.291 --> 01:07:07.708
You all right?

1152
01:07:08.750 --> 01:07:11.041
[sighs] Yeah. kind of exhausted.

1153
01:07:11.125 --> 01:07:15.833
It's like I thought that having this ship
meant our problems would be solved.

1154
01:07:17.750 --> 01:07:20.708
[scoffs] Yeah.

1155
01:07:25.958 --> 01:07:28.541
-Is Mauro sleeping?
-Yeah.

1156
01:07:29.708 --> 01:07:33.250
Or at least he's trying.
He's not doing too good.

1157
01:07:34.791 --> 01:07:38.750
Were you aware that he'd hide
in the engine room to cry every day?

1158
01:07:41.791 --> 01:07:43.833
But he was looking forward
to the next mission.

1159
01:07:43.916 --> 01:07:45.875
And I thought it might be good for him.

1160
01:07:47.958 --> 01:07:49.875
It's like he can't move on.

1161
01:07:56.375 --> 01:07:58.375
[somber music playing]

1162
01:07:59.708 --> 01:08:02.000
That's too bad. your donation
would have been a great help.

1163
01:08:02.083 --> 01:08:04.458
Domi. Please include
these expenses. thanks.

1164
01:08:04.541 --> 01:08:07.291
Um. but did you know
you can get a tax write-off for donations?

1165
01:08:07.375 --> 01:08:10.541
"You wanna destroy the continent."
"Where are they all gonna live?"

1166
01:08:10.625 --> 01:08:12.583
"Has that even crossed your minds?"

1167
01:08:12.666 --> 01:08:14.041
[Nina] The mission is in two weeks.

1168
01:08:14.125 --> 01:08:16.833
but we don't have a first officer
or someone to drive the RHIB.

1169
01:08:16.916 --> 01:08:19.500
We also need someone for the sick bay.
Su needs a break.

1170
01:08:19.583 --> 01:08:22.125
"It's human trafficking and you should all
get what you deserve."

1171
01:08:22.208 --> 01:08:24.041
"You should do time."

1172
01:08:24.125 --> 01:08:26.708
"Traffickers without borders
should die at sea."

1173
01:08:26.791 --> 01:08:29.083
-It's locked. I can't get in.
-What is it?

1174
01:08:29.166 --> 01:08:31.625
We got hacked.
The website. social media. all of it.

1175
01:08:32.291 --> 01:08:34.500
-Do we know who it was?
-Some right-wingers! Who else?!

1176
01:08:34.583 --> 01:08:36.416
Fuck! Shit! Dammit!

1177
01:08:36.500 --> 01:08:37.916
"I saw you on TV."

1178
01:08:38.000 --> 01:08:41.583
"This plan you're so proud of
is a really shitty idea."

1179
01:08:41.666 --> 01:08:44.166
"Seriously. where are they supposed
to go?"

1180
01:08:44.250 --> 01:08:45.541
"What about our jobs and women?"

1181
01:08:46.208 --> 01:08:48.750
What is that? Who went to Hamburg?

1182
01:08:48.833 --> 01:08:51.291
Why is there a receipt
from fucking Hamburg?

1183
01:08:53.500 --> 01:08:54.916
Found this under the sink.

1184
01:08:55.000 --> 01:08:57.500
"Fuck you and your Islamization
of the West."

1185
01:08:57.583 --> 01:09:00.625
"Germany's for Germans. and that's it."

1186
01:09:00.708 --> 01:09:02.041
Lukas.

1187
01:09:02.125 --> 01:09:04.791
The Italian Coast Guard ordered
the Iuventa to the Port of Lampedusa.

1188
01:09:04.875 --> 01:09:06.875
-With only five refugees on board.
-Wait.

1189
01:09:06.958 --> 01:09:08.916
What? That doesn't make any sense.

1190
01:09:09.000 --> 01:09:10.791
-Viola. I've got you on speaker.
-[Viola] <i>Yeah.</i>

1191
01:09:10.875 --> 01:09:12.125
We've got five minors on board.

1192
01:09:12.208 --> 01:09:14.333
and there are four
or five rubber dinghies out there.

1193
01:09:14.416 --> 01:09:16.041
transporting like 500 people.

1194
01:09:16.125 --> 01:09:18.250
We can't assist them if we leave now.

1195
01:09:18.333 --> 01:09:21.666
-Can't you transfer passengers?
-[Sören] <i>Yeah. no. we've tried.</i>

1196
01:09:21.750 --> 01:09:24.500
The Italians said it was out
of the question without a reason.

1197
01:09:24.583 --> 01:09:27.250
We have to head to Lampedusa.
Their tone is raising in their emails.

1198
01:09:27.333 --> 01:09:29.875
They're all. "Follow the orders!"
You know?

1199
01:09:29.958 --> 01:09:32.875
-Right. Where are you right now?
-[Viola] <i>A whole day away from Lampedusa.</i>

1200
01:09:32.958 --> 01:09:34.916
<i>We'll lose two days</i>
<i>getting there and back.</i>

1201
01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:36.541
So we're not doing it.

1202
01:09:36.625 --> 01:09:39.375
No way. We always have
to cooperate with the authorities.

1203
01:09:39.458 --> 01:09:40.875
-It's the law.
<i>-Nina.</i>

1204
01:09:40.958 --> 01:09:43.625
We have to rescue those people.
That's why we're here.

1205
01:09:43.708 --> 01:09:46.291
-Because lives come first.
-What are you trying to say?

1206
01:09:46.375 --> 01:09:49.416
I'm saying we're disregarding the order.
We're staying put.

1207
01:09:50.583 --> 01:09:53.500
You can't. No. If you don't comply.
we will not stand by you.

1208
01:09:53.583 --> 01:09:55.791
<i>You will have stayed</i>
<i>against our explicit orders.</i>

1209
01:09:55.875 --> 01:09:57.416
<i>and we will cancel all future missions.</i>

1210
01:09:57.500 --> 01:10:00.583
We cooperate.
It's the Jugend Rettet core tenet.

1211
01:10:00.666 --> 01:10:03.125
-[Sören] <i>Are you serious right now?</i>
-[both] Yeah.

1212
01:10:06.166 --> 01:10:08.166
[Viola sighs deeply]

1213
01:10:09.875 --> 01:10:11.125
[radio beeps]

1214
01:10:33.708 --> 01:10:37.041
-Hey.
-[gentle music playing]

1215
01:10:38.750 --> 01:10:39.916
[Kitty sighs]

1216
01:10:41.750 --> 01:10:43.750
[doorbell ringing]

1217
01:10:49.333 --> 01:10:51.333
[ringing continues]

1218
01:10:57.333 --> 01:10:58.333
Yeah?

1219
01:10:59.083 --> 01:11:01.083
[footsteps approaching]

1220
01:11:06.083 --> 01:11:07.541
-[man] Hello?
-Hello?

1221
01:11:07.625 --> 01:11:09.208
Refugees. We heard we can live here.

1222
01:11:09.291 --> 01:11:10.458
-Open door. come on!
-What?

1223
01:11:10.541 --> 01:11:13.833
-[knocking]
-[man 2] Open door. open door!

1224
01:11:13.916 --> 01:11:16.250
-Come on. let us in! Hey!
-We're hungry. hey!

1225
01:11:16.333 --> 01:11:18.416
-It's a gang of fascists.
-What?

1226
01:11:18.500 --> 01:11:20.083
-[pounding on door]
-Don't open the door!

1227
01:11:20.166 --> 01:11:22.750
-Hey. are you nuts?
-Leave right now!

1228
01:11:22.833 --> 01:11:25.166
-Who is that?
-A bunch of fascists.

1229
01:11:25.250 --> 01:11:26.375
Why the fuck are you here?!

1230
01:11:26.458 --> 01:11:28.458
-Should we call the cops?
-Yeah! Go call the cops.

1231
01:11:28.541 --> 01:11:33.500
Listen. we're calling the police now.
What the fuck is your problem?!

1232
01:11:33.583 --> 01:11:36.791
-Get out of here! Fuck off. guys!
-That's enough!

1233
01:11:36.875 --> 01:11:39.333
[Kitty] Yes. hi. We've got a bunch
of guys banging at our door

1234
01:11:39.416 --> 01:11:40.875
and yelling at us to let them in.

1235
01:11:40.958 --> 01:11:43.041
-[tense music playing]
-[clicks tongue]

1236
01:11:43.125 --> 01:11:47.208
-[Nina] Please come quick.
-[guys shouting outside]

1237
01:11:47.291 --> 01:11:49.666
We're calling the police.
so go on and fuck off!

1238
01:11:49.750 --> 01:11:52.375
-[Nina] They're still banging.
-[Lukas] Just get out of here!

1239
01:11:52.458 --> 01:11:55.000
-Yeah. okay. thanks. Okay.
-[Lukas] Come on. fuck off already!

1240
01:11:55.083 --> 01:11:57.083
[breathing shakily]

1241
01:11:58.250 --> 01:11:59.458
[Kitty] Get lost!

1242
01:11:59.541 --> 01:12:02.458
-I'll handle this.
-They're not leaving!

1243
01:12:02.541 --> 01:12:05.125
-[Kitty] Get lost!
-Oh!

1244
01:12:05.208 --> 01:12:06.708
[Kitty] Fuck off! Now!

1245
01:12:06.791 --> 01:12:08.500
-[guys laugh]
-[panting]

1246
01:12:08.583 --> 01:12:10.583
[Mauro hyperventilating]

1247
01:12:13.125 --> 01:12:14.625
Mauro. are you all right?

1248
01:12:15.833 --> 01:12:17.916
-Are you okay? Can you hear?
-I can't breathe.

1249
01:12:18.000 --> 01:12:19.250
[Nina] Okay. exhale.

1250
01:12:19.833 --> 01:12:23.125
-Inhale slowly. You're safe.
-[Kitty] Okay.

1251
01:12:23.208 --> 01:12:25.250
-[Lukas] Hey.
-It's fine. They're gone.

1252
01:12:25.333 --> 01:12:29.666
-[Mauro] I can't breathe.
-[exhales deeply] Exhale slowly.

1253
01:12:29.750 --> 01:12:31.000
You're safe.

1254
01:12:34.958 --> 01:12:36.375
[Lukas] It's all good.

1255
01:12:41.916 --> 01:12:43.625
[exhales deeply]

1256
01:12:46.458 --> 01:12:48.458
They're gone now. It's okay.

1257
01:12:53.166 --> 01:12:55.166
[Mauro sighs]

1258
01:13:00.708 --> 01:13:02.541
[Lukas] We stop missions in the winter.

1259
01:13:02.625 --> 01:13:04.166
The refugees don't cross in dinghies.

1260
01:13:04.250 --> 01:13:06.666
The sea gets really dicey.
The weather's too bad.

1261
01:13:06.750 --> 01:13:09.500
We're using the downtime
to tune up the ship.

1262
01:13:09.583 --> 01:13:11.750
And in January.
we're organizing a big meeting

1263
01:13:11.833 --> 01:13:15.083
to go over everything that happened
during our first year at sea.

1264
01:13:16.000 --> 01:13:19.458
The good stuff and the challenges.

1265
01:13:19.958 --> 01:13:22.458
-[mom] Hm. Mm.
-[dad] Mm-hmm.

1266
01:13:22.958 --> 01:13:25.666
-[Lukas] What?
-Nothing.

1267
01:13:26.166 --> 01:13:28.416
-What is it?
-[mom] Nothing.

1268
01:13:29.166 --> 01:13:31.916
Well. I didn't want
to bring this up tonight.

1269
01:13:32.000 --> 01:13:33.375
I'm just concerned.

1270
01:13:33.458 --> 01:13:34.791
You've been doing this two years.

1271
01:13:34.875 --> 01:13:36.500
You said you'd give it one.

1272
01:13:36.583 --> 01:13:39.208
Mm-hmm. So?

1273
01:13:39.291 --> 01:13:43.333
So. Kitty's almost done with her program.
You haven't even started a degree.

1274
01:13:44.458 --> 01:13:47.333
You think I should mention it down there?
I could tell the refugees.

1275
01:13:47.416 --> 01:13:50.083
"Sorry! I gotta move on now.
My mother thinks this isn't honorable."

1276
01:13:50.166 --> 01:13:52.541
-That's not what I meant.
-What <i>did </i>you mean?

1277
01:13:53.666 --> 01:13:56.500
I am only saying
that nearly two years have gone by.

1278
01:13:56.583 --> 01:13:58.541
and I haven't heard from you
in six months.

1279
01:13:58.625 --> 01:14:00.125
So I am worried.

1280
01:14:00.208 --> 01:14:03.458
-You can't go on like this.
-Trust me. I wish I could just stop!

1281
01:14:05.500 --> 01:14:08.208
I'd be thrilled to move on with my life.

1282
01:14:09.041 --> 01:14:12.000
I wish no one needed rescuing anymore
or someone else would do it.

1283
01:14:12.083 --> 01:14:14.375
But no one steps in.

1284
01:14:16.291 --> 01:14:19.708
Governments aren't offering to take over.
They're not helping!

1285
01:14:22.750 --> 01:14:24.333
You're not either.

1286
01:14:26.666 --> 01:14:29.583
You believe giving 500 euros
at Christmas is enough support.

1287
01:14:33.166 --> 01:14:34.958
We won't stop till it changes.

1288
01:14:38.625 --> 01:14:39.625
[quietly] Good.

1289
01:14:44.750 --> 01:14:46.750
[indistinct chatter]

1290
01:14:54.375 --> 01:14:57.625
[Viola] <i>What I don't understand is…</i>
<i>are there charges against us?</i>

1291
01:14:57.708 --> 01:14:59.416
<i>Why do you need to search our ship?</i>

1292
01:14:59.500 --> 01:15:01.291
<i>No. No. it's just routine.</i>

1293
01:15:01.375 --> 01:15:02.583
[Sören] <i>It's not routine.</i>

1294
01:15:02.666 --> 01:15:05.166
<i>And for five minors.</i>
<i>you don't have to search our ship.</i>

1295
01:15:05.250 --> 01:15:08.125
<i>It doesn't make any sense!</i>
<i>Look. our papers are in order.</i>

1296
01:15:08.208 --> 01:15:10.333
<i>Everything is fine.</i>
<i>I really don't get the point.</i>

1297
01:15:10.416 --> 01:15:12.208
[officer] <i>These are routines. Don't worry.</i>

1298
01:15:12.291 --> 01:15:14.708
[Sören] <i>There are people</i>
<i>out at sea. They need our help.</i>

1299
01:15:14.791 --> 01:15:18.375
<i>Otherwise. they're going to die</i>
<i>while we have this discussion here.</i>

1300
01:15:19.208 --> 01:15:22.208
So that's what complying
with the authorities looks like.

1301
01:15:22.291 --> 01:15:25.166
You get pulled from your mission.
and the ship gets searched.

1302
01:15:25.250 --> 01:15:28.250
[Sören] They interviewed us all night
and let us go back the next morning.

1303
01:15:28.333 --> 01:15:30.208
We lost two whole days because of it.

1304
01:15:30.958 --> 01:15:33.666
We had to go there
because we had five minors on board.

1305
01:15:33.750 --> 01:15:36.625
There were hundreds of people
still out there on rubber dinghies.

1306
01:15:36.708 --> 01:15:38.666
We don't know what happened to them.

1307
01:15:38.750 --> 01:15:40.958
But here's the thing.
at that moment like that.

1308
01:15:41.041 --> 01:15:42.625
there's nothing that the coast guard

1309
01:15:42.708 --> 01:15:44.583
or any authority can say.

1310
01:15:44.666 --> 01:15:46.125
We're there to save people.

1311
01:15:46.208 --> 01:15:48.791
Okay. But what did you expect us
to do. then?

1312
01:15:48.875 --> 01:15:51.750
Because ignoring the authorities
is not a good solution.

1313
01:15:51.833 --> 01:15:53.000
Stay and rescue.

1314
01:15:53.083 --> 01:15:55.916
You should have stood by the decision
and let us refuse the orders.

1315
01:15:56.000 --> 01:15:58.041
-It would've been bad.
-This is our ship.

1316
01:15:58.125 --> 01:15:59.708
We are free to do as we please on it.

1317
01:15:59.791 --> 01:16:02.083
But it's not your ship!
It's not ours either.

1318
01:16:02.166 --> 01:16:04.458
You didn't pay for it.
It is not private property.

1319
01:16:04.541 --> 01:16:06.250
It's not ours!

1320
01:16:06.333 --> 01:16:08.541
And all of us know
that you just want to save people.

1321
01:16:08.625 --> 01:16:10.208
but we have to play by the damn rules!

1322
01:16:10.291 --> 01:16:12.791
I'm not doing what I want to.
I'm doing what I have to.

1323
01:16:12.875 --> 01:16:15.000
Well. Jugend Rettet
always has to cooperate.

1324
01:16:15.083 --> 01:16:17.375
I mean. if cooperating means
letting people die out there.

1325
01:16:17.458 --> 01:16:18.875
we shouldn't cooperate.

1326
01:16:18.958 --> 01:16:21.125
It is criminal
to go against the authorities.

1327
01:16:21.208 --> 01:16:23.166
We will lose funding.
and we won't save any lives.

1328
01:16:23.250 --> 01:16:26.708
This silly image you're trying to project
by wearing your designer outfits--

1329
01:16:26.791 --> 01:16:27.833
[both] Viola!

1330
01:16:27.916 --> 01:16:30.208
It's not helping us rescue anyone.
It's an act!

1331
01:16:30.291 --> 01:16:32.166
-You're out of line!
-[Viola] I carry corpses.

1332
01:16:32.250 --> 01:16:34.375
You just sit at your desk
with your spreadsheets.

1333
01:16:34.458 --> 01:16:36.208
Wow. Viola. You don't get it at all.

1334
01:16:36.291 --> 01:16:38.958
Without us here. in Berlin.
you wouldn't have a ship.

1335
01:16:39.041 --> 01:16:41.375
I don't sit here
and sweet-talk for donations.

1336
01:16:41.458 --> 01:16:43.791
I do public relations.
fundraising. advocacy work.

1337
01:16:43.875 --> 01:16:45.166
and read every fucking email.

1338
01:16:45.250 --> 01:16:46.416
I sift through all the hate.

1339
01:16:46.500 --> 01:16:47.958
How dare you say I just sit here!

1340
01:16:48.041 --> 01:16:49.750
I'm killing myself
to get people's support!

1341
01:16:49.833 --> 01:16:52.458
Without all the work we do here.
we wouldn't have a single penny.

1342
01:16:52.541 --> 01:16:56.291
Yeah. but if we let the Italians bully us.
your fucking money's useless!

1343
01:16:56.375 --> 01:16:57.541
Enough!

1344
01:16:58.500 --> 01:17:00.500
This is why we're falling apart.

1345
01:17:00.583 --> 01:17:03.041
You're being really disrespectful
and self-righteous.

1346
01:17:03.125 --> 01:17:06.041
-I just say it how it is.
-Why are you fighting us?

1347
01:17:06.125 --> 01:17:07.000
'Cause we have to.

1348
01:17:08.791 --> 01:17:09.666
[sighs]

1349
01:17:15.333 --> 01:17:17.708
-[lighter clicks]
-She was really shitty in there.

1350
01:17:17.791 --> 01:17:20.250
[scoffs. sighs]

1351
01:17:20.333 --> 01:17:22.083
I spend like all of my time in this place.

1352
01:17:22.166 --> 01:17:24.166
I don't have a life.
and they say I don't care?

1353
01:17:24.250 --> 01:17:27.083
I'm more into my outfits
than saving the migrants who need my help?

1354
01:17:27.166 --> 01:17:29.291
She's all acting
like there's two types of people.

1355
01:17:29.375 --> 01:17:31.500
The ones who work at computers
and those who save lives.

1356
01:17:31.583 --> 01:17:34.958
I hear you. Just try to keep in mind
these are views on the same problem.

1357
01:17:35.041 --> 01:17:36.000
At the end of the day.

1358
01:17:36.083 --> 01:17:37.875
the point is to get out there
and save lives.

1359
01:17:37.958 --> 01:17:42.666
I'm perfectly aware of what goes on at sea
even though I don't go on the missions!

1360
01:17:43.375 --> 01:17:46.041
But the people here
don't seem to care about that!

1361
01:17:46.125 --> 01:17:48.791
Y'know. before it was all.
"We can do it!" That time's passed.

1362
01:17:49.375 --> 01:17:51.541
Nobody wants anything
to change around here.

1363
01:17:51.625 --> 01:17:53.541
Sure. they want the migrant problem
to be solved.

1364
01:17:53.625 --> 01:17:55.875
They don't want to actually help
with any of it though.

1365
01:17:55.958 --> 01:17:57.458
They want it to just disappear!

1366
01:17:57.958 --> 01:18:00.583
How can they see that welcoming people
could bring us together

1367
01:18:00.666 --> 01:18:02.000
if it's tearing us apart?

1368
01:18:02.083 --> 01:18:04.791
[sighs] I think I should work elsewhere.

1369
01:18:06.291 --> 01:18:07.958
-Sorry.
-Domi.

1370
01:18:08.666 --> 01:18:09.708
Domi!

1371
01:18:12.375 --> 01:18:13.666
[sighs]

1372
01:18:16.916 --> 01:18:18.916
{\an8}[energetic music playing]

1373
01:18:47.458 --> 01:18:48.541
Hey.

1374
01:19:02.000 --> 01:19:04.125
[woman sighs] Fucking Libyan Coast Guard.

1375
01:19:04.208 --> 01:19:05.375
Oh shit.

1376
01:19:06.375 --> 01:19:09.416
-They're shooting at them.
-[gunfire on video]

1377
01:19:10.375 --> 01:19:13.458
-Do you know where Sören and Viola are?
-Upstairs.

1378
01:19:13.541 --> 01:19:14.541
Thanks.

1379
01:19:18.791 --> 01:19:21.750
[Viola] Last year's militia are now
official Libyan Coast Guard.

1380
01:19:21.833 --> 01:19:24.791
[Sören] Yeah. Europe's actually training
and financing them.

1381
01:19:25.625 --> 01:19:27.250
[Viola] Everything's changing. It's crazy.

1382
01:19:27.333 --> 01:19:29.000
No one wants anything to do with refugees.

1383
01:19:29.083 --> 01:19:32.291
[Sören] European countries want
to block the Mediterranean route.

1384
01:19:32.375 --> 01:19:35.750
That's why they ordered us to Lampedusa.
They don't want witnesses.

1385
01:19:35.833 --> 01:19:37.583
[Viola] Yeah. They want us to back down.

1386
01:19:37.666 --> 01:19:40.500
[Sören] But there are as many dinghies
out there as last year.

1387
01:19:40.583 --> 01:19:41.541
They come in waves.

1388
01:19:41.625 --> 01:19:45.041
Sometimes we see eight
or nine boats out there at the same time.

1389
01:19:45.125 --> 01:19:47.333
[Viola] It's insane. Hundreds of people.

1390
01:19:47.416 --> 01:19:49.458
They all die if no one rescues them.

1391
01:19:50.166 --> 01:19:52.166
[thunder rumbles]

1392
01:19:58.750 --> 01:20:00.458
[passengers clamoring]

1393
01:20:06.666 --> 01:20:07.750
[Lukas] Sören!

1394
01:20:08.583 --> 01:20:09.708
Sören!

1395
01:20:09.791 --> 01:20:11.458
-Sören!
-What?

1396
01:20:11.541 --> 01:20:14.916
There's way too many of them!
Where's the fucking coast guard?

1397
01:20:15.000 --> 01:20:18.708
[Sören] They said they were on their way!
But that was hours ago!

1398
01:20:18.791 --> 01:20:20.541
We can't handle it all alone!

1399
01:20:20.625 --> 01:20:23.583
Get the people from there.
onto the life raft.

1400
01:20:23.666 --> 01:20:25.375
We'll fill the raft. okay?

1401
01:20:25.458 --> 01:20:27.833
Everybody. I need your help.

1402
01:20:28.416 --> 01:20:29.833
Pull the people inside.

1403
01:20:30.708 --> 01:20:32.000
Okay.

1404
01:20:32.500 --> 01:20:35.000
I need space. Guys. I need space!

1405
01:20:35.916 --> 01:20:39.000
-[man panting]
-[Lukas] I got him! I got him!

1406
01:20:39.625 --> 01:20:43.500
Come on. let me through.
Sorry. sorry. sorry.

1407
01:20:43.583 --> 01:20:46.208
[passengers clamoring]

1408
01:20:47.833 --> 01:20:49.416
What's up with the coast guard?

1409
01:20:49.500 --> 01:20:51.583
They saw two other boats
that need rescuing.

1410
01:20:51.666 --> 01:20:53.333
What about other ships? The navy?

1411
01:20:53.416 --> 01:20:55.791
-Apparently. no one can.
-No one can help?

1412
01:20:57.166 --> 01:20:59.125
-Okay.
-Hang on. Sören.

1413
01:21:00.333 --> 01:21:02.583
We've got to get everyone on deck
and dump the life rafts.

1414
01:21:02.666 --> 01:21:04.625
-No way. We can't.
-We've got to.

1415
01:21:04.708 --> 01:21:06.833
This boat won't move
in this weather if we don't!

1416
01:21:06.916 --> 01:21:08.291
It's the way to fight the waves.

1417
01:21:08.375 --> 01:21:11.291
Viola. The deck is full.
Why don't you get that?

1418
01:21:11.375 --> 01:21:14.458
-There's no more room!
-I get it. but it's the only way.

1419
01:21:14.541 --> 01:21:17.833
-One big wave and it's all over.
-Yeah. I know that!

1420
01:21:22.125 --> 01:21:23.333
Fuck.

1421
01:21:26.958 --> 01:21:30.875
[under breath] God fucking damn it.
Lord help us.

1422
01:21:30.958 --> 01:21:33.166
Get everyone up! Get them all up there!

1423
01:21:34.583 --> 01:21:37.583
Lukas! Lukas! Maik! Come up here!

1424
01:21:37.666 --> 01:21:41.291
We have to get everyone up here.
Everyone below deck!

1425
01:21:41.375 --> 01:21:43.958
Here. come on! Come up!

1426
01:21:44.041 --> 01:21:45.625
Get below deck!

1427
01:21:45.708 --> 01:21:48.583
Get everyone down there!
Get everyone below deck!

1428
01:21:48.666 --> 01:21:50.416
One after the other!

1429
01:21:51.500 --> 01:21:54.125
[panicked clamoring]

1430
01:21:54.208 --> 01:21:57.166
Get inside. You can come here.
Come here. come here.

1431
01:21:57.250 --> 01:21:59.375
Okay. go inside. Go inside!
Go inside. go inside.

1432
01:21:59.458 --> 01:22:01.500
[woman sobbing]

1433
01:22:01.583 --> 01:22:03.750
She's really weak. She's really weak.

1434
01:22:03.833 --> 01:22:06.375
Watch your head. Watch your feet. please!

1435
01:22:06.458 --> 01:22:07.666
Go there.

1436
01:22:07.750 --> 01:22:09.791
Okay. be careful. Try to hold on.

1437
01:22:09.875 --> 01:22:12.208
Be careful! Watch your step. please.
Go there.

1438
01:22:12.291 --> 01:22:13.583
Please move back a bit.

1439
01:22:13.666 --> 01:22:15.833
-One by one!
-Back up!

1440
01:22:15.916 --> 01:22:17.791
Slower. Careful. please.
Please. take care!

1441
01:22:20.166 --> 01:22:23.083
Spread out! Everybody spread out!

1442
01:22:24.958 --> 01:22:28.666
Please. everyone needs to wait a minute!
And be careful!

1443
01:22:28.750 --> 01:22:30.416
Please slow down!

1444
01:22:30.500 --> 01:22:32.208
Try to make space for everyone.

1445
01:22:32.291 --> 01:22:35.208
[Viola] <i>Mayday. mayday.</i>
<i>This is Iuventa. Iuventa. Iuventa.</i>

1446
01:22:35.291 --> 01:22:37.208
<i>I have 400 people on board.</i>

1447
01:22:37.291 --> 01:22:40.708
With the current weather situation.
I'm not able to safely navigate.

1448
01:22:40.791 --> 01:22:44.791
Please. I need immediate assistance.
I'm not able to get out of this situation.

1449
01:22:44.875 --> 01:22:46.791
<i>Mayday! Mayday! Mayday!</i>

1450
01:22:46.875 --> 01:22:48.291
[screaming]

1451
01:22:48.375 --> 01:22:50.541
[somber music building]

1452
01:22:50.625 --> 01:22:51.666
[Sören] Man overboard!

1453
01:22:54.875 --> 01:22:57.833
[Lukas] Go back to your vessel! Go back!

1454
01:23:00.916 --> 01:23:02.333
[Lukas] Go back to the--

1455
01:23:03.250 --> 01:23:04.958
[man gasping]

1456
01:23:05.041 --> 01:23:08.500
Okay. come here! Come here! Grab my hand!

1457
01:23:09.000 --> 01:23:12.041
Hold on tight! I'm here for you!
Take my hand!

1458
01:23:12.125 --> 01:23:13.541
[yelps]

1459
01:23:27.708 --> 01:23:30.041
[man] Over here! Come on! Take my hand!

1460
01:23:30.125 --> 01:23:31.750
Come on! Come on. now!

1461
01:23:35.000 --> 01:23:37.000
[Lukas grunts. panting]

1462
01:23:46.666 --> 01:23:48.166
God help us.

1463
01:23:53.541 --> 01:23:57.666
[screams continue in distance]

1464
01:23:57.750 --> 01:24:01.500
[Lukas] <i>We were out there</i>
<i>for 48 hours in total.</i>

1465
01:24:01.583 --> 01:24:03.791
<i>We were left to ourselves completely.</i>

1466
01:24:03.875 --> 01:24:06.250
<i>No ships came to help.</i>
<i>The Coast Guard never showed up.</i>

1467
01:24:06.333 --> 01:24:07.625
<i>Neither did the Navy.</i>

1468
01:24:07.708 --> 01:24:09.958
<i>Our ship was so packed.</i>
<i>we couldn't fit anyone else.</i>

1469
01:24:10.041 --> 01:24:12.083
<i>We had to watch people drown.</i>

1470
01:24:12.166 --> 01:24:15.125
<i>We ran out of space on board</i>
<i>and life vests. We had nothing.</i>

1471
01:24:15.208 --> 01:24:18.458
<i>We were devastated.</i>
<i>We were over capacity. People kept coming.</i>

1472
01:24:18.541 --> 01:24:20.375
<i>We couldn't help them all.</i>

1473
01:24:20.458 --> 01:24:23.666
<i>A container ship finally appeared</i>
<i>and offered us a hand.</i>

1474
01:24:23.750 --> 01:24:25.458
<i>With that crew's help. we got to catch up</i>

1475
01:24:25.541 --> 01:24:27.125
<i>with another rescue mission.</i>

1476
01:24:27.208 --> 01:24:29.583
<i>Folks from Save the Children. a big ship.</i>

1477
01:24:29.666 --> 01:24:32.208
<i>The people we'd rescued got on.</i>
<i>That's what we do.</i>

1478
01:24:32.291 --> 01:24:34.833
You're still in the Mediterranean.
Whereabouts?

1479
01:24:34.916 --> 01:24:36.000
<i>In Malta.</i>

1480
01:24:36.083 --> 01:24:38.333
<i>Yeah. We're getting ourselves ready</i>
<i>for the next mission.</i>

1481
01:24:38.416 --> 01:24:39.708
Bergmann. what are you thinking?

1482
01:24:39.791 --> 01:24:42.125
You believe policies are sufficient
in dealing with this?

1483
01:24:42.208 --> 01:24:45.583
Uh… Well. let me just start
by saying that these young folks

1484
01:24:45.666 --> 01:24:48.666
are doing some extraordinary work
down there.

1485
01:24:48.750 --> 01:24:50.875
And look. I don't mean
to question their motives.

1486
01:24:50.958 --> 01:24:53.125
They are surely honorable.
They really are.

1487
01:24:53.208 --> 01:24:57.250
But as far as we see it.
these rescue ships are also pull factors.

1488
01:24:57.333 --> 01:25:00.291
You mean they actually cause
these migrants

1489
01:25:00.375 --> 01:25:02.708
to risk their lives
in the hopes of being saved?

1490
01:25:02.791 --> 01:25:03.625
Exactly.

1491
01:25:03.708 --> 01:25:05.958
They're willing to do just about anything

1492
01:25:06.041 --> 01:25:07.875
to get out of their dire situations.

1493
01:25:07.958 --> 01:25:11.583
They'll risk their lives if a ship
is supposed to bring them to Europe.

1494
01:25:11.666 --> 01:25:13.916
<i>-But it doesn't happen like that at all.</i>
-Mr. Weiland?

1495
01:25:14.000 --> 01:25:16.166
<i>I mean. I'm sorry but it's not true.</i>

1496
01:25:16.250 --> 01:25:18.041
<i>People don't get onto these dinghies</i>

1497
01:25:18.125 --> 01:25:21.208
<i>thinking an NGO rescue ship</i>
<i>is waiting out there to save them.</i>

1498
01:25:21.291 --> 01:25:23.625
<i>No. people do it</i>
<i>because they're in war zones.</i>

1499
01:25:23.708 --> 01:25:26.958
<i>They're living in countries</i>
<i>that outlaw their sexuality or religion.</i>

1500
01:25:27.041 --> 01:25:28.958
<i>They can't even feed their families.</i>

1501
01:25:29.041 --> 01:25:32.625
<i>You have to be pretty desperate</i>
<i>to get on a rubber dinghy like that.</i>

1502
01:25:32.708 --> 01:25:36.458
<i>One would only venture out to sea</i>
<i>for a matter of life or death.</i>

1503
01:25:36.541 --> 01:25:39.458
<i>Once on board our boat.</i>
<i>they're not interested in welfare checks.</i>

1504
01:25:39.541 --> 01:25:42.625
<i>All they want is to write to their mothers</i>
<i>to tell them they survived.</i>

1505
01:25:42.708 --> 01:25:44.250
And what is your response

1506
01:25:44.333 --> 01:25:48.875
to the allegations that there are rescuers
working with the human traffickers?

1507
01:25:48.958 --> 01:25:52.166
That there's a whole line of communication
that takes place

1508
01:25:52.250 --> 01:25:54.041
before each dinghy departs.

1509
01:25:54.125 --> 01:25:56.416
<i>That's not true either.</i>
<i>These allegations are false.</i>

1510
01:25:56.500 --> 01:25:58.625
<i>The authorities are aware of that.</i>

1511
01:25:58.708 --> 01:26:03.083
<i>That's all false information</i>
<i>aimed at discrediting our mission.</i>

1512
01:26:03.166 --> 01:26:04.791
<i>Of course. people end up believing it</i>

1513
01:26:04.875 --> 01:26:07.333
<i>since it's repeated so much</i>
<i>on talk shows like this.</i>

1514
01:26:07.416 --> 01:26:10.833
<i>There's never any communication</i>
<i>in advance with them.</i>

1515
01:26:10.916 --> 01:26:14.291
We heard that you leave them boats
and motors sometimes.

1516
01:26:14.375 --> 01:26:15.750
<i>We're in the middle of the sea.</i>

1517
01:26:15.833 --> 01:26:19.208
<i>So. of course. we can't always destroy</i>
<i>the rubber dinghies during rescues.</i>

1518
01:26:19.291 --> 01:26:24.375
<i>We're busy saving people in danger</i>
<i>because… because it's our priority.</i>

1519
01:26:25.375 --> 01:26:28.791
<i>Our mission is saving lives.</i>
<i>Not handling boats.</i>

1520
01:26:36.375 --> 01:26:42.541
{\an8}MALTA. LATE JULY 2017

1521
01:26:53.166 --> 01:26:55.166
[gentle music playing]

1522
01:27:00.416 --> 01:27:02.583
[Kitty sighs]

1523
01:27:05.083 --> 01:27:07.416
[both chuckle softly]

1524
01:27:09.916 --> 01:27:12.708
-Wow. you look like shit.
-[scoffs] Yeah.

1525
01:27:14.833 --> 01:27:16.416
-Let's go for a walk.
-Mm-hmm.

1526
01:27:18.958 --> 01:27:20.166
[sighs]

1527
01:27:21.458 --> 01:27:24.416
So what's the conference.
uh… you're going to?

1528
01:27:24.500 --> 01:27:27.125
-Where is it again?
-Uh. in Syracuse. in Sicily.

1529
01:27:27.208 --> 01:27:28.333
Right.

1530
01:27:28.416 --> 01:27:31.250
The conference is focused
on international human rights.

1531
01:27:37.333 --> 01:27:42.125
Nina mentioned the situation down here
is getting really hard.

1532
01:27:42.208 --> 01:27:44.875
[scoffs] That's an understatement.
for sure.

1533
01:27:44.958 --> 01:27:46.333
This is a war.

1534
01:27:48.500 --> 01:27:51.416
They're fighting the refugees.
so they're fighting us too.

1535
01:27:52.458 --> 01:27:56.416
The Italian government has asked us
to sign a code of conduct.

1536
01:27:56.500 --> 01:27:58.916
They want the police to ride along
on the Iuventa

1537
01:27:59.000 --> 01:28:02.375
so they can… interrogate the refugees
as soon as they board.

1538
01:28:02.458 --> 01:28:06.416
Odds are. they're just going to ask.
"Who was driving the dinghy?"

1539
01:28:06.500 --> 01:28:10.250
And someone will proudly say
they were in charge.

1540
01:28:10.333 --> 01:28:15.208
feeling heroic. and they'll get locked up
for 20 years for human trafficking.

1541
01:28:15.291 --> 01:28:18.500
Most NGOs already signed it.
but we're not gonna do that.

1542
01:28:21.125 --> 01:28:23.416
I know exactly how they're gonna answer.

1543
01:28:41.291 --> 01:28:42.500
[Kitty sighs]

1544
01:28:49.208 --> 01:28:50.958
My ferry's gonna leave soon.

1545
01:28:59.500 --> 01:29:01.500
[hesitates]

1546
01:29:03.708 --> 01:29:05.708
When's your next mission?

1547
01:29:07.208 --> 01:29:09.125
Uh… tomorrow.

1548
01:29:09.708 --> 01:29:10.916
[Kitty sighs]

1549
01:29:15.833 --> 01:29:17.166
[huffs]

1550
01:29:17.250 --> 01:29:18.750
[sniffles]

1551
01:29:25.208 --> 01:29:26.875
[sighs deeply]

1552
01:29:31.458 --> 01:29:34.791
[exhales] Take care of yourself.

1553
01:29:34.875 --> 01:29:36.875
[tender music rises]

1554
01:29:41.708 --> 01:29:44.250
[indistinct chatter]

1555
01:29:45.125 --> 01:29:48.125
[Sören] Excuse me.
Why are you bringing two people on board?

1556
01:29:48.208 --> 01:29:50.333
-[officer speaking Italian]
-[Sören] No. Don't.

1557
01:29:50.416 --> 01:29:53.750
Where did you find them?
What do you want us to do with them now?

1558
01:29:53.833 --> 01:29:56.083
-[guard speaking Italian]
-[Sören] No. It <i>is </i>a problem.

1559
01:29:56.166 --> 01:29:57.791
'Cause we don't know why they're here.

1560
01:29:57.875 --> 01:29:59.000
[officer speaking Italian]

1561
01:29:59.083 --> 01:30:01.875
[Sören] What should we do now?
No. I don't understand.

1562
01:30:02.916 --> 01:30:04.083
Who are they?

1563
01:30:04.166 --> 01:30:06.666
Apparently. two brothers from Syria.

1564
01:30:06.750 --> 01:30:09.666
[Lukas] With nice suitcases?
Brought here by the Coast Guard.

1565
01:30:11.083 --> 01:30:13.250
So we need to take them to Lampedusa?
For real?

1566
01:30:13.333 --> 01:30:16.791
-Yeah.
-That's nuts.

1567
01:30:20.083 --> 01:30:23.375
-[Paula] We're just trying to--
-Okay. stop. Um…who are you?

1568
01:30:23.458 --> 01:30:25.541
-We are brothers from Syria.
-Brothers. okay.

1569
01:30:25.625 --> 01:30:27.125
-[Paula] Lukas.
-Just wait a second.

1570
01:30:27.208 --> 01:30:30.833
Honestly. you don't look like brothers.
Can you stop filming for a second?

1571
01:30:30.916 --> 01:30:32.875
What is this? What are you doing here?

1572
01:30:32.958 --> 01:30:35.041
We're doing interviews for a documentary.

1573
01:30:35.125 --> 01:30:36.541
[scoffs] Documentary?

1574
01:30:36.625 --> 01:30:39.750
-About the situation of refugees.
-Okay. no. Uh. please take it down. okay?

1575
01:30:39.833 --> 01:30:42.541
We're not doing an interview.
We're not doing a documentary here.

1576
01:30:42.625 --> 01:30:45.500
-Take it down. Hey! Take it… Fuck!
-What?

1577
01:30:45.583 --> 01:30:47.291
This is insane.

1578
01:30:47.875 --> 01:30:52.541
{\an8}LAMPEDUSA. 02 AUGUST 2017

1579
01:30:53.458 --> 01:30:55.458
[crowd clamoring]

1580
01:31:01.750 --> 01:31:03.416
Who's the captain here?

1581
01:31:04.708 --> 01:31:08.791
-This ship is under police investigation.
-Why?

1582
01:31:08.875 --> 01:31:11.833
I'm sorry. madam.
But you have to leave the ship.

1583
01:31:13.541 --> 01:31:15.625
-What's the reason?
-Please.

1584
01:31:15.708 --> 01:31:18.333
The whole crew has
to leave the ship. Now.

1585
01:31:18.416 --> 01:31:21.000
-Come on.
-We've done nothing wrong.

1586
01:31:21.083 --> 01:31:24.208
There is no reason
for us to leave this ship.

1587
01:31:24.291 --> 01:31:26.875
-[officers speaking Italian]
-[Viola] I mean…

1588
01:31:28.083 --> 01:31:31.208
Are we under arrest?
What? Please don't touch me.

1589
01:31:31.291 --> 01:31:33.291
[indistinct chatter]

1590
01:31:41.250 --> 01:31:43.250
[sounds distort]

1591
01:31:51.083 --> 01:31:53.083
[cell phone vibrating]

1592
01:31:54.958 --> 01:31:58.666
Nina? Wait. we're putting you on speaker.

1593
01:31:59.583 --> 01:32:01.791
-All right.
-[Nina] <i>Okay. Where are you?</i>

1594
01:32:01.875 --> 01:32:03.541
By the boat. They're searching it.

1595
01:32:03.625 --> 01:32:06.208
[Nina] <i>I know. The phones</i>
<i>are ringing off the hook here.</i>

1596
01:32:06.291 --> 01:32:08.541
They're seizing the ship now.

1597
01:32:08.625 --> 01:32:11.000
We're going to get charged
with human trafficking.

1598
01:32:11.875 --> 01:32:13.291
[quietly] What?

1599
01:32:13.375 --> 01:32:16.208
[Nina] <i>That's what the Italian authorities</i>
<i>told the press.</i>

1600
01:32:16.291 --> 01:32:18.916
They've got a 400-page indictment
against us.

1601
01:32:19.000 --> 01:32:21.416
-[sighs]
-It's all over the media already.

1602
01:32:21.500 --> 01:32:23.500
[Maik] Yup. look at all this.

1603
01:32:25.583 --> 01:32:27.625
So. they knew before us?

1604
01:32:27.708 --> 01:32:30.250
Looks like they were fully prepared.

1605
01:32:32.125 --> 01:32:35.750
I found a lawyer from Borderline Europe
who's on vacation on Lampedusa.

1606
01:32:35.833 --> 01:32:37.750
She's headed to the indictment hearing
right now.

1607
01:32:37.833 --> 01:32:39.625
<i>and you need to meet with her.</i>

1608
01:32:41.291 --> 01:32:42.791
Okay. thanks.

1609
01:32:42.875 --> 01:32:46.208
-[Nina] <i>Take care of yourselves.</i>
-We will. Bye.

1610
01:32:46.291 --> 01:32:48.375
[officer] Yes. Take them all.

1611
01:32:59.125 --> 01:33:02.250
[woman] <i>First. I have to ask you</i>
<i>to switch off your mobile devices. please.</i>

1612
01:33:02.333 --> 01:33:05.041
<i>And I see that you have a fridge.</i>

1613
01:33:05.125 --> 01:33:07.625
<i>Would you be so kind</i>
<i>to actually switch them off</i>

1614
01:33:07.708 --> 01:33:09.375
and put them in there. please?

1615
01:33:11.916 --> 01:33:13.291
Thank you.

1616
01:33:13.375 --> 01:33:17.083
They tapped over 40 phones.
Lawyers. priests. journalists…

1617
01:33:17.166 --> 01:33:18.583
It's all in here.

1618
01:33:19.958 --> 01:33:23.916
There are three criminal offenses
brought against the Iuventa crew.

1619
01:33:24.000 --> 01:33:30.083
One suggests a direct handover of people
from the smugglers to the Iuventa.

1620
01:33:30.166 --> 01:33:32.916
The other one.
a hand gesture. like waving.

1621
01:33:33.000 --> 01:33:37.083
Which is supposed to prove communication
and establish relationship

1622
01:33:37.166 --> 01:33:38.416
between you and them.

1623
01:33:38.500 --> 01:33:39.708
Hand-waving?

1624
01:33:39.791 --> 01:33:43.000
They seized our ship
because someone waved a hand?

1625
01:33:43.791 --> 01:33:44.791
Yes.

1626
01:33:44.875 --> 01:33:46.625
-[scoffs]
-And… the third one

1627
01:33:46.708 --> 01:33:52.291
accuses you of returning
three refugee boats to Libyan smugglers.

1628
01:33:53.625 --> 01:33:58.750
{\an8}This all results in a charge of aiding
and abetting unauthorized immigration.

1629
01:33:58.833 --> 01:34:00.875
which means people smuggling.

1630
01:34:01.875 --> 01:34:03.583
How did they get the photos?

1631
01:34:03.666 --> 01:34:06.166
Obviously they had someone
on board who took them.

1632
01:34:06.250 --> 01:34:09.125
There was a spy?
There was a spy on board the other ship?

1633
01:34:09.208 --> 01:34:11.875
-We just pulled the boats out of the way.
-Yeah.

1634
01:34:11.958 --> 01:34:14.375
We tried not to jeopardize
the rescue operation.

1635
01:34:15.041 --> 01:34:19.416
If you only look at the photo.
it tells a different story.

1636
01:34:19.500 --> 01:34:22.041
And that's the story
that they told the press.

1637
01:34:22.125 --> 01:34:23.458
What?

1638
01:34:23.541 --> 01:34:25.250
Oh. and there is one more thing.

1639
01:34:25.333 --> 01:34:29.000
The files indicate
that the Italian authorities

1640
01:34:29.083 --> 01:34:34.416
have transcripts of conversations
on board of the Iuventa.

1641
01:34:34.500 --> 01:34:36.416
-[both] What?
-You mean they bugged us?

1642
01:34:36.500 --> 01:34:37.666
Mm.

1643
01:34:37.750 --> 01:34:41.375
That's why they ordered us
to Lampedusa. To bug us.

1644
01:34:42.458 --> 01:34:45.250
[sighs] Shit. man.

1645
01:34:46.500 --> 01:34:50.500
What happens if we're…
uh. what's the word?

1646
01:34:50.583 --> 01:34:52.166
-Convicted.
-Yeah.

1647
01:34:52.833 --> 01:34:55.250
People smuggling is a serious accusation.

1648
01:34:55.333 --> 01:35:00.541
So if the court rules against you.
you might have to go to jail.

1649
01:35:05.583 --> 01:35:08.291
-[sighs]
-How long?

1650
01:35:08.375 --> 01:35:10.916
At least five. up to 20 years.

1651
01:35:11.750 --> 01:35:16.041
And 15.000 euro fine per person
brought into Italy.

1652
01:35:19.416 --> 01:35:20.416
[sighs]

1653
01:35:25.416 --> 01:35:27.500
[somber music playing]

1654
01:36:32.333 --> 01:36:34.333
[message alerts playing]

1655
01:36:43.041 --> 01:36:45.041
[line ringing]

1656
01:36:49.250 --> 01:36:52.291
-[Lamin] <i>Hello. my friend.</i>
-[chuckles] Hello. Lamin.

1657
01:36:52.375 --> 01:36:54.958
[in German] <i>I tried to call you</i>
<i>five times.</i>

1658
01:36:55.041 --> 01:36:57.666
[in English] I saw that. yeah.
You already speaking German. or what

1659
01:36:57.750 --> 01:37:01.208
[in German] Yes. I got a course!
Intensive course.

1660
01:37:01.291 --> 01:37:05.833
And I told myself. "If you want to go
to school. you have to learn German."

1661
01:37:06.416 --> 01:37:09.583
-[in English] That's fantastic.
-[In German] <i>Yes. it's hard.</i>

1662
01:37:09.666 --> 01:37:12.333
<i>-It's really a difficult language.</i>
-[chuckles]

1663
01:37:12.416 --> 01:37:15.041
<i>But now I can stay in Germany.</i>

1664
01:37:15.125 --> 01:37:18.791
I'll finish school.
and then I'll do an apprenticeship.

1665
01:37:18.875 --> 01:37:20.666
Industrial mechanic.

1666
01:37:21.250 --> 01:37:25.000
[in English] Industrial mechanics?
Cool. [chuckles]

1667
01:37:25.083 --> 01:37:28.458
<i>And I called you because I wanted</i>
<i>to tell you something</i>

1668
01:37:28.541 --> 01:37:33.250
I couldn't have done that
without you all. You know?

1669
01:37:33.333 --> 01:37:38.166
<i>That day on your ship</i>
<i>was the happiest day in my life. you know?</i>

1670
01:37:38.250 --> 01:37:41.750
<i>And now. I'm getting educated.</i>

1671
01:37:41.833 --> 01:37:43.708
<i>I can follow my dreams.</i>

1672
01:37:43.791 --> 01:37:46.666
And I can do all of that because of you.

1673
01:37:49.166 --> 01:37:51.000
<i>That's why I wanted to thank you.</i>

1674
01:37:52.166 --> 01:37:53.666
<i>That's why I'm calling.</i>

1675
01:37:57.083 --> 01:37:59.375
<i>-What is wrong. my friend?</i>
-Nothing.

1676
01:38:00.500 --> 01:38:02.750
<i>-What is it?</i>
-Lamin. they seized our ship.

1677
01:38:02.833 --> 01:38:03.666
<i>What?</i>

1678
01:38:03.750 --> 01:38:06.541
Yeah. they're saying we work
with smugglers together.

1679
01:38:06.625 --> 01:38:09.500
<i>-But you don't.</i>
-No. I know. I know we don't.

1680
01:38:09.583 --> 01:38:12.250
<i>-I tell them that you didn't do that.</i>
-[chuckles]

1681
01:38:12.333 --> 01:38:14.583
Yeah. that would… that would be great.

1682
01:38:14.666 --> 01:38:17.458
<i>I tell them that you did not work</i>
<i>with the smugglers.</i>

1683
01:38:17.541 --> 01:38:20.125
<i>I was there. I can testify.</i>

1684
01:38:20.208 --> 01:38:22.541
<i>We all do. All of us.</i>

1685
01:38:23.458 --> 01:38:27.958
Without you. we all would have died.
For sure.

1686
01:38:28.750 --> 01:38:32.208
<i>You saved us and now. we'll save you.</i>

1687
01:38:32.291 --> 01:38:34.958
Lamin. that… that would be amazing.

1688
01:38:36.166 --> 01:38:37.291
Really.

1689
01:38:40.166 --> 01:38:42.166
[indistinct chatter]

1690
01:38:43.916 --> 01:38:47.291
What if the refugees are our witnesses?

1691
01:38:48.166 --> 01:38:51.125
They were there.
They can say that they were in distress.

1692
01:38:51.208 --> 01:38:54.666
That they fought for their lives
and we didn't collaborate with smugglers.

1693
01:38:54.750 --> 01:38:57.250
I mean. we don't know
where they are today.

1694
01:38:57.333 --> 01:39:00.416
They probably live all over Europe
if they are still in Europe.

1695
01:39:00.500 --> 01:39:03.583
-We can find them. I'm sure. Right?
-[sighs]

1696
01:39:03.666 --> 01:39:05.666
[energetic music playing]

1697
01:39:09.750 --> 01:39:11.541
When are we allowed to leave Lampedusa?

1698
01:39:11.625 --> 01:39:13.375
Who are the people
in charge of the Iuventa?

1699
01:39:15.458 --> 01:39:18.208
So I would suggest
the three of you stay here

1700
01:39:18.291 --> 01:39:20.666
and wait for the decision
of the authorities.

1701
01:39:21.750 --> 01:39:26.708
<i>They might come up to question you</i>
<i>or come up with an arrest warrant.</i>

1702
01:39:26.791 --> 01:39:29.791
Why can't we just fly back?
I mean. what can they do?

1703
01:39:29.875 --> 01:39:31.791
Arrest us because we tried to flee?

1704
01:39:31.875 --> 01:39:32.791
[lawyer] <i>Yes.</i>

1705
01:39:32.875 --> 01:39:35.208
[Viola] <i>What?</i>
<i>But no. they can't arrest us.</i>

1706
01:39:35.291 --> 01:39:37.875
<i>We are all European citizens.</i>

1707
01:39:37.958 --> 01:39:41.125
I mean. they just seized our ship
without any reason.

1708
01:39:41.208 --> 01:39:42.833
[lawyer] Exactly.

1709
01:39:42.916 --> 01:39:47.125
<i>I think the crew can leave.</i>
<i>They can't force them to stay.</i>

1710
01:39:47.208 --> 01:39:50.875
<i>But… I don't know</i>
<i>what will happen to the three of you.</i>

1711
01:39:50.958 --> 01:39:54.250
Great. I guess we're stuck here.

1712
01:40:00.083 --> 01:40:02.000
I'll be. uh. right back.

1713
01:40:02.083 --> 01:40:06.041
-Lukas!
-[Lukas] I know how to get us out of here!

1714
01:40:12.875 --> 01:40:15.375
[Lukas] <i>I knew Mauro</i>
<i>had a sailing license.</i>

1715
01:40:15.458 --> 01:40:17.875
<i>So he got on the next flight</i>
<i>to Mallorca with Nina.</i>

1716
01:40:17.958 --> 01:40:18.791
Good luck.

1717
01:40:18.875 --> 01:40:21.291
<i>Dressed like tourists.</i>
<i>they chartered a boat</i>

1718
01:40:21.375 --> 01:40:25.291
<i>and sailed nonstop for five days</i>
<i>and five nights straight to Lampedusa.</i>

1719
01:40:25.958 --> 01:40:28.875
<i>While the rest of the crew</i>
<i>flew back to Berlin.</i>

1720
01:40:28.958 --> 01:40:31.791
<i>Nina and Mauro smuggled us off the island.</i>

1721
01:40:32.791 --> 01:40:34.791
[hopeful music playing]

1722
01:40:41.500 --> 01:40:43.500
[hopeful music fades]

1723
01:40:46.791 --> 01:40:49.625
[Lukas] <i>For a brief moment. we were free.</i>

1724
01:40:54.458 --> 01:40:57.416
We're officially in international waters.
You can come up.

1725
01:40:59.083 --> 01:41:00.666
-Let's celebrate.
-[Nina] Okay.

1726
01:41:00.750 --> 01:41:02.458
I know this is super inappropriate.

1727
01:41:02.541 --> 01:41:04.708
but we were given this bottle
when we rented the boat.

1728
01:41:04.791 --> 01:41:06.416
-So let's enjoy.
-Cheers.

1729
01:41:13.500 --> 01:41:14.500
To us.

1730
01:41:22.083 --> 01:41:24.166
[gentle music playing]

1731
01:41:24.250 --> 01:41:27.041
<i>The case became one of the longest</i>
<i>and most elaborate</i>

1732
01:41:27.125 --> 01:41:31.083
<i>against a civilian rescue organization</i>
<i>in history.</i>

1733
01:41:31.166 --> 01:41:33.125
[crowd chanting]

1734
01:41:33.208 --> 01:41:36.791
[prosecutor] Were you responsible
for communication during the operations?

1735
01:41:36.875 --> 01:41:38.333
Among others. yes.

1736
01:41:38.416 --> 01:41:42.000
So your crew relied on secret.
encrypted channels? Is that correct?

1737
01:41:42.083 --> 01:41:45.875
We used WhatsApp.
It's not secret. It's practical.

1738
01:41:45.958 --> 01:41:48.708
<i>The Italian authorities wanted</i>
<i>to set a precedent with us.</i>

1739
01:41:48.791 --> 01:41:50.958
<i>despite there being no evidence</i>
<i>to support their claims.</i>

1740
01:41:51.041 --> 01:41:53.875
Witnesses reported strong light signal
from your ship.

1741
01:41:53.958 --> 01:41:55.208
What were you signaling?

1742
01:41:55.875 --> 01:41:58.250
Nothing. We were scanning
for boats in distress.

1743
01:41:58.958 --> 01:42:00.208
Using searchlights at night

1744
01:42:00.291 --> 01:42:02.583
is standard procedure
in every rescue operation.

1745
01:42:02.666 --> 01:42:04.833
[Lukas] <i>They called us</i>
<i>the "taxis of the sea."</i>

1746
01:42:04.916 --> 01:42:06.083
[speaking indistinctly]

1747
01:42:06.166 --> 01:42:09.083
[Lukas] <i>Their goal was</i>
<i>to discredit and silence us.</i>

1748
01:42:09.916 --> 01:42:13.333
<i>Every transfer was documented.</i>
<i>reported to the authorities.</i>

1749
01:42:13.416 --> 01:42:15.791
<i>You can check the records.</i>
<i>the e-mails. the phone logs…</i>

1750
01:42:15.875 --> 01:42:18.291
<i>It's all there. Everything is on record.</i>

1751
01:42:18.375 --> 01:42:21.125
[Lukas] <i>We continued trying</i>
<i>to find those we'd rescued.</i>

1752
01:42:21.208 --> 01:42:24.416
<i>Anyone willing to testify</i>
<i>that we were innocent.</i>

1753
01:42:28.458 --> 01:42:31.291
<i>Many were living in temporary camps</i>
<i>and shelters.</i>

1754
01:42:31.375 --> 01:42:34.125
<i>far from their families and dreams</i>
<i>of a safe future.</i>

1755
01:42:36.833 --> 01:42:38.666
[Rose gasps]

1756
01:42:38.750 --> 01:42:40.625
[Lukas] <i>They were all willing</i>
<i>to testify for us.</i>

1757
01:42:40.708 --> 01:42:42.208
-Hi.
-[Lukas] Hello. Rose.

1758
01:42:42.291 --> 01:42:45.291
[Rose] We were captured
by the Libyan militias in the desert.

1759
01:42:45.375 --> 01:42:46.958
And taken to prison.

1760
01:42:47.041 --> 01:42:49.875
They beat us and left us
without food for days.

1761
01:42:49.958 --> 01:42:52.500
Many women were forced into prostitution.

1762
01:42:52.583 --> 01:42:56.958
When I close my eyes. I…
I still hear the scream of people.

1763
01:42:57.041 --> 01:42:59.541
Objection. None of this
is relevant to this case.

1764
01:42:59.625 --> 01:43:02.375
Overruled. It's relevant. Please go on.

1765
01:43:03.791 --> 01:43:07.000
[Lamin] We were drifting for days.
abandoned at sea.

1766
01:43:07.083 --> 01:43:08.916
before the Iuventa found us.

1767
01:43:09.000 --> 01:43:13.666
There was no direct handover.
Or collaboration with the smugglers.

1768
01:43:13.750 --> 01:43:17.458
Without them. I would not be here.

1769
01:43:17.541 --> 01:43:20.416
We would not be here to tell our story.

1770
01:43:20.500 --> 01:43:22.166
We would be dead.

1771
01:43:23.541 --> 01:43:26.333
The Iuventa people saved our lives.

1772
01:43:26.833 --> 01:43:28.166
That's what they did.

1773
01:43:29.875 --> 01:43:35.291
[Lukas] <i>On April 19. 2024.</i>
<i>after over 40 hearings and seven years.</i>

1774
01:43:35.375 --> 01:43:37.416
<i>the judge announced the verdict.</i>

1775
01:43:39.625 --> 01:43:42.166
The evidence presented in this case

1776
01:43:42.250 --> 01:43:45.958
speaks with absolute clarity
and completeness

1777
01:43:46.041 --> 01:43:50.125
to the absence of the offenses
brought against the defendants.

1778
01:43:51.208 --> 01:43:56.708
When individuals risk their lives
to escape torture and enslavement.

1779
01:43:57.333 --> 01:43:59.291
this court cannot punish those

1780
01:43:59.375 --> 01:44:03.750
whose actions were aimed
towards ensuring their survival.

1781
01:44:04.416 --> 01:44:06.375
The act of saving lives at sea

1782
01:44:06.458 --> 01:44:10.708
is not and has never been
a criminal offense.

1783
01:44:10.791 --> 01:44:12.791
-[Lukas] Yeah!
-[group exclaims]

1784
01:44:13.583 --> 01:44:16.083
[Lukas] <i>We were acquitted on all charges.</i>

1785
01:44:18.750 --> 01:44:21.208
[gentle music rises]

1786
01:44:21.291 --> 01:44:22.791
[Lukas] <i>I can only speak for myself.</i>

1787
01:44:22.875 --> 01:44:25.375
<i>but I will always rescue people</i>
<i>from drowning.</i>

1788
01:44:26.291 --> 01:44:28.291
[gentle music swells]

1789
01:44:29.875 --> 01:44:31.875
<i>Helping is not a crime.</i>

1790
01:44:34.208 --> 01:44:36.208
<i>It is an act of humanity.</i>

1791
01:44:37.250 --> 01:44:39.250
[energetic music playing]

1792
01:44:44.375 --> 01:44:46.750
{\an8}BETWEEN 2016 AND 2017.

1793
01:44:46.833 --> 01:44:51.541
{\an8}THE IUVENTA CREW SAVED OVER 23.000 LIVES.

1794
01:44:52.458 --> 01:44:55.500
{\an8}DURING THE SEVEN YEARS OF THE TRIAL
AGAINST THE IUVENTA

1795
01:44:55.583 --> 01:44:58.833
{\an8}TENS OF THOUSANDS OF PEOPLE DROWNED
IN THE MEDITERRANEAN.

1796
01:44:59.458 --> 01:45:02.416
{\an8}WITH THE ALMOST ONE MILLION EUROS
SPENT ON THE TRIAL

1797
01:45:02.500 --> 01:45:07.500
{\an8}"JUGEND RETTET" COULD HAVE CONTINUED
SAVING LIVES IN THE MEDITERRANEAN

1798
01:45:07.583 --> 01:45:09.375
{\an8}FOR FOUR MORE YEARS.

1799
01:45:10.083 --> 01:45:13.458
{\an8}OR BOUGHT SIX MORE SHIPS LIKE THE IUVENTA

1800
01:45:13.541 --> 01:45:16.833
{\an8}AND USED THEM FOR RESCUE OPERATIONS.

1801
01:45:18.083 --> 01:45:21.541
{\an8}THE IUVENTA RUSTED IN THE PORT OF TRAPANI.

1802
01:45:21.625 --> 01:45:26.375
{\an8}IN 2024. IT WAS RETURNED
TO "JUGEND RETTET" AS A WRECK.

1803
01:45:27.125 --> 01:45:31.875
{\an8}MANY MEMBERS OF THE IUVENTA CREW
REMAINED ACTIVE DESPITE THE CHARGES

1804
01:45:31.958 --> 01:45:35.166
{\an8}AND WORKED
WITH OTHER RESCUE ORGANIZATIONS.

1805
01:45:35.916 --> 01:45:38.458
{\an8}IN 2020. THE IUVENTA CREW WAS AWARDED

1806
01:45:38.541 --> 01:45:43.291
{\an8}THE AMNESTY INTERNATIONAL
HUMAN RIGHTS PRIZE FOR THEIR WORK.

1807
01:45:44.125 --> 01:45:51.125
{\an8}THEIR STORY INSPIRED MANY OTHERS
TO HELP PEOPLE IN NEED.

1808
01:45:52.333 --> 01:45:57.208
THIS FILM IS DEDICATED TO ALL THE PEOPLE
WHO LOST THEIR LIVES IN THE MEDITERRANEAN.

1809
01:45:57.291 --> 01:46:00.625
TO THOSE WHO SURVIVED.
AND TO ALL THOSE WHO HELPED THEM.

1810
01:46:05.166 --> 01:46:10.250
23.000 LIVES

1811
01:52:00.958 --> 01:52:03.458
[music fades]

1812
01:52:03.541 --> 01:52:08.541
Subtitle translation by: Diana Renker

1813
01:52:09.305 --> 01:53:09.517
